MP3 players versus cell phones
We will advise you on how to choose
While almost any cell phone can read MP3 files, no MP3 player can telephony.
It's clear from this that it's better to buy only the phone.
Nevertheless, there are many reasons for acquiring a self-reading machine.
The choice depends entirely on the way of use and the requirements of the future owner.
You may not buy a high-quality expensive record player to listen to Maxim Turbulenc's latest album.
First of all, these musical products do not come out as LP's and from a qualitative point of view there is no objective reason for this.
But if you find hard-rock, jazz, or blues records on your shelves, you probably dream of such a turntable.
It also works with portable music, i.e. compressed music or simply in MP3 format.
Here too there are price and quality categories.
It may be unacceptable for some to spend 8,000 kroner on a reader, just as a Pink Floyd fan may have a hard time digesting the 20 kroner headphones on the market.
Two extremes between which there's enough room for everyone.
There's a lot to choose from.
It's the battery life that counts.
Some high-quality music players can do much more than just read music, but that's something that cell phones don't do even by accident.
There is no other modern device that is as universal as the mobile phone.
Along with the primary functions, calling and texting, it can read music and video, record both, and it has a camera, sometimes better, sometimes worse, and maybe even browsing.
And if we consider smartphones and handhelds, you'll also have a miniature computer in your pocket.
It's a small miracle because no refrigerator can make a grill and no television can photograph anything.
The universality of the mobile phone also brings disadvantages.
The more features you use on your phone, the sooner the indicator on the screen will require charging.
And reading music takes up a lot of energy.
Few cell phones can play music for more than 12 hours, usually, and much less.
In this respect, music players (especially the simpler ones) are much more effective.
As for the cheap phones, don't count on them lasting more than a few hours.
If you add to this, from time to time, a few calls, get another battery charger at work for safety, this applies even to the most expensive appliances.
But you won't have this problem with an MP3 player, even the worst ones last at least nine hours of continuous operation on a single charge.
Another problem arises when downloading music to your mobile phone.
Unfortunately, only a limited number of devices have the universal USB port and not all of them can be connected to the computer without special software.
Of course, music can be recorded directly to the memory card, but only a few memory readers are able to do so without an adapter for the minicards that are not used in mobile phones.
The readers, with a few exceptions (iPods), do not require any special software.
Just fill the unit with music via USB from the computer.
Most cell phones and readers create a multimedia library of their own, sorted by artist name, album name, genre or user rating.
Some devices only reproduce the tree structure of the folders, similar to the Explorer tool in Windows, and some can do both (iriver, Samsung, Sony, Cowon, smartphones with operating system).
Readers are easier to handle, cell phones can do more.
When choosing a particular device, you should be especially concerned with its battery life, memory capacity, sound quality and type of output, and, of course, ease of use.
If you need music mainly in the background and you listen to it every day only briefly on the tram, you just need an ordinary MP3 reader mobile phone.
Now, that's possible, obviously, with any cell phone.
You don't have to worry too much about what formats the phone or the reader recognizes.
MP3 players support all of them, so the majority of the music that comes to you globally will be in that format.
In addition to this format, which is among the most common, the vast majority of devices support music in WMA format.
AAC (the format used by Apple and its iPods) is missing.
The best cell phones also allow, for example, the purchase of music online.
Simply visit the corresponding pages of the mobile operator (or another provider) and buy the song or album.
This same service could be a valid argument for buying a mobile phone-reader.
Unfortunately, the operators' offer is meager and is usually limited to the radio's one-hit wonder.
The prices are not exactly cheap.
But it is generally assumed that this very way of selling music (whether via GSM, the internet or the wireless internet) will dominate the music industry in the future.
Most people carry their cell phones with them all the time.
Anyone who comes to listen to something goes into their pocket while the MP3 player is forgotten at home.
But it also depends on whether you're always wearing your headphones or at least your wireless headphones.
If not, you can use the built-in player that almost every cell phone, but only a small fraction of MP3 players, have.
Perhaps the biggest advantage of reader-mobiles will be, for many, the price.
The cheapest ones usually cost less than 3,000 kroner.
For three or four thousand crowns you can buy a very decent Walkman.
Usually, however, you will be limited by the absence of a common headphone input.
The best and technically most equipped mobile phones, and also with the 3.5 mm jack for common headphones, cost up to 15 thousand kroner.
The advantage of the readers is, among other things, the ease of handling.
The simpler ones are not necessarily the cheapest (see our choice) but they are really handy for anyone to handle.
The minimal functions, the similarity of the handling to the common stereo or perhaps the record player, is obvious.
There is no danger of accidentally hitting the start of the mobile Internet network and consequently a giant bill for data transmission.
Which device to take
Even the cheapest mobile phones (for example Vodafone 527) have as a rule a slot for interchangeable memory cards (of the type M2, microSD etc.).
The purchase of the corresponding card is also included in the 2 000 kroner.
But be careful.
The basic models only support cards with a maximum capacity of 2GB.
Only the high-end ones can handle 8GB memory cards.
If you already have a mobile phone and want to buy a cheap MP3 player, get Cowon, Creative, Sony, Samsung, Emgeton or iriver.
According to the capacity (max. 2 GB) you should not spend more than 1 100 kroner.
If you are one of the most demanding listeners, you should take specialized mobile phones - walkman (Sony Ericsson, some Nokia and Samsung).
These devices have individual MP3 keyboards and the convenience of the service thus approaches the same MP3 player.
Sony Ericsson has come a long way in this area, with its Walkman line of mobile phones having the same range of use as MP3 players sold separately.
MP3 players of the above brands offer the same service and the same price range up to 4 000 kroner, but with a larger memory capacity (up to 16 GB) and battery life (usually 15 hours, usually up to 35 hours).
The first virtual operator will be in the Czech Republic as early as this year.
Maybe you should .
The Czech mobile phone market is perhaps quite mature and our operators offer virtually all the services of their Western European counterparts.
However, something is missing here - a virtual operator that forces traditional ones to lower the price.
Maybe he won't be gone for long.
We have written many times on Mobil.cz that Czech operators are among the most expensive in Europe.
This was eventually confirmed by ČTÚ, which pointed out that the price of SMS is higher in the Czech Republic than in the rest of the Union.
The latest steps by the European Commission in the field of regularizing roaming charges may create a paradoxical situation - for some customers of Czech mobile operators, SMS abroad will cost less than at home.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic are so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there is no competition that would really want to start the fight.
It may sound absurd, but we also have three mobile networks here and coverage well over 100 percent.
The mobile phone operators, on the other hand, like to complain that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
This is also often emphasized by the head of the Czech Telecommunications Council (ČTÚ), Pavel Dvořák, who has sometimes in the past expressed that there is no place for another operator in the Czech Republic.
It is perhaps true that the traditional operator with his own network probably no longer has many possibilities (otherwise it would perhaps be difficult to find other frequencies).
But there is still another possibility - the virtual operator.
The entry of virtual operators into the market has led to a significant price reduction, to which the traditional operators would then have to react.
At the same time, even before sharks like Tesko Mobile and Virgin Mobile entered the market, there were similar voices in Britain as there are here.
But it has been shown that there is a place for such operators and that they can be really successful.
We must not go too far for examples.
In February this year we informed you of the arrival of the virtual operator Mobilking in Poland.
In just six months, the operator has managed to gain more than 100 000 customers and become the fifth largest local operator.
At the same time, Mobilking is backed by the Penta financial group, to which Ufon belongs in the Czech Republic.
The advantage of virtual operators is the possibility of concentrating on a much more concrete target group.
In other words, they require far fewer customers than a traditional operator to be able to operate effectively.
They do not have to bear relatively high costs for the creation, operation and maintenance of the mobile network.
So in the world, virtual operators are usually low-cost, they offer cheap calls and SMS, which is often in balance with the more restricted offer of services.
For example, Tesco Mobile in the UK offers SMS at least half the cost of its competitors.
But as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, it can be a pretty good move to bet on a target group.
This operator is targeting men specifically, so to speak.
"Real men choose Mobilking as a carrier that they like and can trust", says David Seibertz, CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, which produces this virtual carrier.
It is difficult to say whether we can claim a similar concept as in Poland.
Vodafone press spokesman Miroslav Čepický doubts this: "The Czech market is relatively small for a fragmented approach, which most virtual operators rely on.
Moreover, it is relatively saturated in terms of services.
No chance in the Czech Republic, say mobile network operators
But it seems almost certain that if there is ever going to be an operator in the Czech Republic it will not be Mobilking.
'There is talk of expanding this successful project, but in the Czech Republic the negotiations are not very promising.
The launch of Mobilking will take place in other countries in our area", Jana Studničková, press spokesperson for the Penta financial group, told Mobile.cz in a telephone conversation.
It thus indirectly confirmed that the current operators in the Czech Republic are definitely not very supportive of this thinking.
On the contrary, they try to do everything so that no potential competitor is created.
The GTS Novera group has been making no secret of its interest in launching a virtual operator for some time, as it would like to take another step towards becoming a real competitor of Telefónica O2 in the field of corporate customers.
"We have a great interest in being able to offer our customers not only fixed but also mobile telecommunications services.
And the sooner the better.
We have repeatedly negotiated this possibility with all Czech mobile operators.
We have already made progress in negotiations with some of them", says Pavel Kaidl, spokesman for the group.
So maybe there will be better times to come.
The first virtual operator is expected to be available by the end of the year.
For now, however, an impenetrable wall of silence surrounds his creation.
'At the moment we do not believe that there is room in the Czech market for the creation of a full-fledged virtual operator.
The Czech market, unlike other markets, is very specific.
So far, no one with a complex and serious project has approached us", said Vlastimil Sršeň from Telefónika O2's press section in a statement to Mobil.cz.
The specificity of the Czech market is also used by other operators.
T-Mobil spokesperson Martina Kemrová adds in a rare nod to the O2 statement: "We have not noticed any viable and mutually beneficial commercial projects that we can continue to build on".
He adds: "A virtual operator is unlikely to appear on the T-Mobile network by the end of the year.
We would have had to have a concrete agreement on the table by now, so that we could consider it on the horizon".
Vodafone focuses instead on meeting its 3G licence requirements.
"We are open to negotiations with potential virtual operators, especially in the field of cost-sharing and infrastructure.
We consider that, from the customer's point of view, the most productive.
Vodafone's main strategy in this area is to find a partner to build a joint network for high-speed mobile internet".
The competent authorities - with the operators involved
The attitude of the mobile operators is easy to understand, the entry of another operator would mean increased competition, would lead to lower prices and thus to lower profits.
So why facilitate the rise of such a competitor?
The troubles surrounding the creation of U:fon testify that when operators care about something they know how to row from the same side.
Perhaps the pressure was high against ČTÚ at the time of the creation of U:fon towards the company of T-Mobile.
This is evidenced by the publicly available information on the ČTÚ web pages.
But now U:fon itself serves as an argument for not accepting the virtual operator.
Martina Kemrová observed: 'The competitive environment in the mobile telephony market has been recently enhanced by the entry of the fourth mobile operator into the market.
With regard to the typology of the mobile market in the Czech Republic it is obvious that the entry of another competitor would place high demands on it and above all on its services.'
The attitude of mobile operators is, however, surprisingly lacking in any interest on the part of the Czech regulatory bodies.
It is not just the attitude of the CTU which, unfortunately, in the Czech Republic - unlike in Great Britain and other developed countries - has no competence to interfere with economic competition.
The Commission has also been asked to provide information on the implementation of the new competition rules.
But this has taken its typical position on the whole issue.
'The entry of the virtual operator into the mobile telephony market would be possible after the conclusion of the contract for the rental of the necessary infrastructure between the mobile operator and the virtual operator.
No such contract has been concluded so far because the offer from potential buyers has probably not been attractive enough for traditional operators", said Kristián Chalupa from the external relations section of ÚOHS in response to our question.
Such a statement by the representatives of the operators is perhaps not surprising.
But from the office that has to protect the interests of consumers and also take care that nobody takes advantage of their position on the market, it is more than a delicate matter.
Especially when Kristián Chalupa adds: "Outside the country where virtual operators are common, we can observe that their entry into the market has contributed to lower prices for mobile telephony services".
But of course the pressure on the proper functioning of the market environment and the lowering of prices are not in the interests of ÚOHS.
What is really shocking in the whole situation is the almost thrilling harmony of these three operators resulting from their reactions.
The question of whether this is really just a coincidence arises on its own.
The same price for all petrol is the result of coincidence and competition.
'The Section has found no evidence of anti-competitive behaviour in this respect and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way.
No operator has a dominant position and therefore no corresponding increased responsibility for its behaviour on the market.
The telecommunications regulator may also be lacking the necessary tools to open up the mobile network market to virtual operators", Chalupa said in his statement.
The interpretation of market dominance is one of the many points of controversy.
There is, of course, the analysis of relevant markets by ČTÚ, according to which telecommunications is the only market from the point of view of economic competition.
In such a market, of course, no Czech operator has a dominant position.
But some legal experts offer a different approach - the agreement of the network operator is always required for the creation of a virtual operator.
And the mobile operator has - after all - a monopoly on its network.
So for a certain portion it must be dominant.
But even if we do not accept this argument, it should be a bit alarming for ÚOHS that three mobile operators are proceeding in such a strangely similar way.
At the same time, the complaints from the interested parties (including the aforementioned company GTS Novera) show that during the negotiations with all operators they encounter very similar obstacles.
Delegating responsibility to ČTÚ in telecommunications is a fairly common trick by which ÚOHS keeps itself out of the whole thing.
We have seen this in some similar cases.
Unfortunately, the expansion of ČTÚ's rights in the field of economic competition in telecommunications was not promoted until the recently passed updating of the Telecommunications Act, despite the fact that many experts expected this to improve the situation.
The representatives of the ÚOHS must be well aware of this, but perhaps their interests lie elsewhere.
You can do it when no one's looking
But what we don't notice is the operation of these pseudo-virtual operators, some of which even exist in the Czech mobile networks.
These are companies which publish their price lists for mobile telephone services which are only partially public.
These are usually companies that do multi-level marketing.
So for example Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and a number of others offer their own mobile phone services.
The price lists of these companies usually reach only the people who are pre-determined.
The magic lies in the fact that the company is a typical business customer, which orders a large number of SIM cards.
As a major customer, he receives special price offers (and other).
The problem is that the commercial conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit such a pre-sale.
'If the cases you mention occur, which we will look into, it could be a breach of the contractual conditions, and it could lead to the termination of cooperation with this company,' Martina Kemrová answered the question in question.
But it is unlikely that such activity would not reach the ears of those responsible for mobile phone operators.
Especially in the cases of the three companies mentioned, there may be thousands of customers.
No operator can simultaneously defend himself against such an attitude.
In other words, they make a substantial profit from the activity of these companies and at the same time - unlike the real operators - they are not harmed in any way by their official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický warns of possible problems: "The law allows such speculation, but only a negligible percentage of customers use the services of these companies.
They also have to accept that the SIM card in their phone is not registered in their name, so they cannot have full access to it like regular customers of mobile operators".
But this should be a little strange for the CTU.
In addition, another issue arises for the OHIM.
If mobile operators turn a blind eye to such an attitude, why do they block the creation of the virtual operator?
It should be added that the rights of the ÚOHS are strong enough to expose such activities and if they do not want to, they will not have to be satisfied with the explanation of the operators who have no idea of all this and whose commercial conditions prohibit it.
When we 're not expensive anymore
As has been mentioned several times in the text, the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market has led to a significant reduction in the price of services.
At the same time, in virtually all the countries where operators were born, the traditional operators tried to prevent their creation in some way.
The arguments they used were virtually identical - too small market, too saturated border, problems with quality of service etc.
But in developed countries, it is precisely in these cases that regulatory bodies have intervened in defense not of mobile operators but of their customers.
Both formal measures and informal pressure have led to the creation of the first virtual operator, and others have followed.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulatory bodies are throwing the whole case like a hot potato.
In our experience we cannot get rid of the feeling that the lack of clarity of competence in these cases is more than comforting.
But we're not giving up.
If the information behind the scenes is correct and the virtual operator will appear very soon, the Czech mobile phone market will be back on track.
If one of the operators had agreed to set up a virtual mobile operator alone, it is unlikely that ÚOHS would be immune to the rejection (discrimination) of the other operators concerned.
And we may stop calling at higher prices than the rest of Europe.
The new Czech anthem has four new versions.
Choose the Best One
Listen to the four new versions of the Czech national anthem.
On the occasion of the Day of the recognition of the Czech State, Prime Minister Mirek Topolánek on Sunday solemnly presented the new recordings of the national anthem "Kde domov můj".
The new recording of the anthem was made by the orchestra of the National Theatre under the direction of Jiří Bělohlávek.
There are four versions available  solo with male or female voice, chorus step and the instrumental edition.
The choir is under the direction of Kateřina Kněžínková and Adam Plachetka.
The authors of the hymn revisions are Otakar Jeremiáš and Jaroslav Krček.
On the website iHNed.cz you can listen to all four versions.
Bělohlávek considers the Czech national anthem one of the most beautiful hymns.
Earlier he told the radio "Český rozhlas" that he has chosen specifically to sing the solo variants, the singers with the most representative young voices, who are expressive and popular.
"From the beginning I tried to make sure that both of them, and the choir, had clear diction, that the text was well understood, that they were in harmony", he said.
Then the national anthem will celebrate its 175th anniversary next year.
The song "Kde domov můj" was first performed in 1834 on the stage of the Stavovskéh theatre in the original opera Fidlovačka by Josef Kajetán Tyl accompanied by the music of František Škroupa.
It has gained popularity and people have spontaneously taken it over.
The first stanza of the song after the founding of Czechoslovakia in 1918 then became the natural part of the national anthem.
It remained one of the seven national symbols even after the birth of the autonomous Czech Republic.
