The MHD in Prague will accompany you for the first time with an electronic ID card.
Wednesday, October 1, 2008 will be written in the history of the Prague Transport Company as the date when the first passengers will board the metro, tram and bus instead of the paper ticket with an electronic card in their pocket.
Right now , there are about 100,000 people who have their own Opencard card that can get it .
Passengers can buy the 30-day and 90-day annual cards (which will be valid from 1 January 2009) and at the same time have their card recharged at the Infopoint and at the offices of the Transport Company and at the metro stops Muzeum, Můstek, Nádraží Holešovice, Anděl, Roztyly, Letňany, Kobylisy, Rajská zahrada, Kačerov and Luka.
The vouchers can be bought from yesterday on the Internet at the Transport Company's website www.dpp.cz.
More than 400 customers had used the service by this afternoon.
Those who start using the service via the Internet can completely forget about the counters at the metro stops where they used to have to wait in long lines for paper tickets.
The cut-out is purchased via the Internet and is recharged on the Opencard at one of the twelve branches of the Municipal Library.
"In these places, passengers have a counter with trained staff who will help them with their online purchases and will also record the credit on their card", said Martin Opatrný, spokesman for the project.
In addition, in libraries, it will be possible to upload the electronic vouchers to the Opencard ATMs and self-service machines installed at the entrances to the metro.
What are these ATMs like?
They are red, resembling ticket erasers, and passengers have already noticed them at the metro stops Roztyly, Budějovická, I. P. Pavlova, Florenc and Vltavská.
"There are now five in the whole city but by the end of the year there should be eighty", concluded Opatrný.
The cash register will be checked by the driver instead of the ATM.
The ATM service that will be operational from tomorrow is very simple.
Just enter your Opencard and once you've paid the coupon, it'll load.
Electronic cards are valid from tomorrow not only in the capital but also in its surroundings.
That is to say, on the city lines of trains and buses numbered 300 to 499, which the inhabitants of the municipalities of Central Bohemia take to reach the capital.
'In the trains added to Prague's integrated transport, there are controllers with card readers to check the validity of the time and zone,' explained the way in which tickets are checked by Filip from the organisation Ropid, which fixes the timetables of Prague's public transport.
City buses have card readers integrated into the driver's cab.
During the ascent, it is therefore necessary not only to show the driver the card, but also to put the Opencard at the designated point next to the cash register.
The driver checks the validity of the coupons loaded.
"If the passenger needs to check the validity of the loaded vouchers, there is nothing easier than asking the driver for this type of information", Drápal added.
Passengers who take city buses and will not remember, when the validity of the coupon expires, can go back to the self-service ATMs, where the coupons are loaded on the card.
Here, information on the validity of their documents will be displayed on the screen of the device.
The Sudeten Germans wanted a referendum from the U.S.
The Sudeten Germans in 1945 asked to include Šumava in the United States.
This is shown by the letter deposited in the South Bohemian Scientific Library.
If we cannot be part of Germany or Austria, we want to at least live under the patronage of the United States.
With this wish, it is said, that groups of Sudeten Germans appealed to the President of the United States in 1945.
This is further evidenced by a letter preserved in a private archive and now deposited in the Scientific Library of South Bohemia.
The Germans in Český Krumlov ask in the letter to the American president not to allow the return of the "Šumava district"  occupied by Hitler on the basis of the Munich agreement to Czechoslovakia.
"We understand the situation and we want to be sure of the promises that the American units will arrive on German territory not as oppressors and enemies, but as liberators", the letter signed with the words "People who care about the fate of Šumava with all their heart" reads.
