4. But how could it be if, when they behave in our way, they have our feelings?
For some years now, the Internet journal "Edge" has been publishing articles by well-known scientists.
6. SPIEGEL ONLINE presents a series of selected answers to the question: "What do you believe is true, without being able to prove it?"
I believe that animals have feelings or other states of consciousness, without me or anyone else having been able to prove it so far, since we cannot even prove that other humans have consciousness.
But in this case, we have to at least hope that all human brains have the same basic configuration.
As soon as we turn to other species and ask questions about feeling or consciousness in general, we enter into unworkable territory, because the reference frame doesn't match.
When a rat is in a dangerous situation, it does the same things that other animals do, which is it pretends to be dead, it runs away, or it attacks.
People behave in a similar way, which some scientists understand to be a comparable subjective feeling.
I can't believe this.
Two aspects of the brain structure make it difficult for us to convey our feelings to animals.
On the one hand, the lateral prefrontal cortex is often linked with human consciousness, the associated circuits (this because of its direct participation in short-term memory and executive and control functions).
In man this large area is much more developed than in other primates and among other creatures it seems to be completely lacking.
At least in those aspects of our consciousness that depend on the prefrontal cortex, including knowledge, who we are, and the ability to plan and make decisions, it is thus admittedly grounded in the assumption that man is even different from other primates.
Another dramatic peculiarity should be seen in the way man speaks: since a large part of life is connected with language, it is often said to be linked to consciousness.
In this case, animals could be excluded.
Although consciousness is not dependent on language, it would affect it so that the animal's consciousness, as it is made, certainly differs greatly from the circumstances of our consciousness.
So it's hard to find out how consciousness might be seen in other animals.
If it is not possible to measure it as an internal and subjective thing, to analyze it through one's own experience because of the special hardware, their research will give us great problems.
Most interpretations refer to the content of conscious experience, but apart from this there is another aspect of consciousness to which science would be easier to access.
One could analyze the processes of animal consciousness without regard to their contents, and this is precisely what happens in studies of short-term memory in primates, especially in the example of visualization.
So by this principle, which Christof Koch and Francis Crick follow, we move first to the neural correlates of consciousness than to the causal mechanisms: both could be identical but not necessarily.
Interestingly, this principle also highlights the value of the prefrontal cortex for implementing visualization.
What, then, is the outline for feelings?
I attribute them to the fact that an emotional system like fear is activated in one of its conscious brain activities.
What we refer to as "fear" is therefore the mental state in which we find ourselves when the activity of the defense system located in the brain (or of its consequences, such as the body's reactions) occupies the working memory.
In this view, feelings are closely connected to the regions of the cortex that characterize primates and especially humans.
With the speaking nature subtle nuances of feeling are created, because we with the help of words and grammar can distinguish and categorize situations, to describe them to others.
