Pankseep argues that what appears to rats and humans as fear probably feels that way to the senses in both cases: but how could it be verified that rats and humans feel the same thing when they behave in a similar way?
A cockroach in danger runs away as if he too feels fear?
In my eyes, the mere similarity of behavior cannot yet demonstrate any vital similarity.
And that's why the neural comparison continues to help: rats and humans have similar paleoencephalans, cockroaches don't even have a brain.
