Getting the Hispanic voters to vote for you is a tricky business.
Barack Obama's education projects are a significant example.
Mr. Obama's campaign notes that, "African-American and Latino students are significantly less likely to graduate than white students", which is true.
To combat these shortcomings in achieving the goals, Obama's education plan specifically advocates, among other things, "transitional bilingual education" for English learners.
Yet the question for Obama is whether his commitment to bilingual education, which emphasizes classroom instruction in languages other than English, does not take into account his interest in bridging learning gaps.
Take, for example, Sixth Street Prep, an elementary school in East Los Angeles County.
The students at the school are mostly Hispanic and low-income.
More than a third of the students, many of whom are newcomers, are studying English.
But among fourth graders, an astonishing 100 percent of students did the Advanced Placement test in the 2008 state mathematics exam.
An equally astonishing 93 percent of fourth graders passed the English-language-arts-proficiency test.
This incredible result was achieved using a different ingredient than Mr. Obama's favorite.
Sixth Street emphasizes review and practice, constant skill evaluation and a "no excuses" attitude.
Also, and this is where Mr. Obama should take note, according to Linda Mikels, Sixth Street's director, the school's obstructive approach to English students is "full immersion".
The use of English emphasizes the almost exclusive use of English in the context of education.
Mrs. Mikels, who opposes bilingual education, told me, "We had a fantastic success with a student who had just come from Mexico and if you had entered the class 12 months later you would not have been able to identify who it was".
"It works", he observed, "for us it works".
Would Obama take a school like Sixth Street Prep as a model and replicate it in other Hispanic-majority schools with English students?
The school's achievements make that question very easy to answer, but the educational policy in his own party (the National Education Associations is a longtime supporter of bilingual education) and his own continued support for bilingual education make it difficult to predict Mr. Obama's answer.
While he agrees that immigrants should study English, Obama recently made the argument trivial when he said people should stop worrying about "English-only" legislation.
