If Obama really wants to close these achievement gaps, he should carefully consider the educational models that work rather than belittling or trivializing them.
Oil drops sharply renews economic fear
Oil prices fell sharply on Monday amid concerns that even the U.S. bailout of financial markets may not be able to lift the economy.
Crude futures are down 7 percent to $99.80 a barrel on the New York Mercantile Exchange in the morning trading.
Prices have dropped more than $20 a barrel since last Monday.
Over the past two weeks, commodities markets have been rocked by financial turmoil on Wall Street, and by a couple of powerful hurricanes in the Gulf of Mexico.
After peaking at $145.26 a barrel in June, prices had fallen to almost $90 a barrel earlier this month, before rising again amid tremendous uncertainty in financial markets.
Anxiety gripped investors again on Monday even after congressional leaders said they had reached an agreement over the weekend on the biggest bailout in history.
The news was clouded by fresh concerns that the financial crisis was far from over.
In the latest installment of the gradual merger, Citigroup will buy the banking operations of Wachovia Corporation, the government said Monday.
At the same time, the Belgian, Dutch and Luxembourg governments partially nationalised the European financial conglomerate Fortis.
Barclays Capital analysts said that the frenzied weekend trading that had led to a bailout deal "seemed to have failed to revive market sentiment".
As the economic situation worsens, demand for commodities, including oil, is expected to ease.
"The outlook for global equity, interest rates and exchange rate markets has become uncertain", Deutsche Bank analysts wrote in a note to investors.
"We believe that the raw materials will not be able to escape the contagion.
From a raw material perspective our most pressing concern is how far the American virus will spread globally and specifically to China".
Bank analysts lowered their expectations for next year as oil consumption declines due to the slowdown in economic growth, reducing oil and gas price forecasts by about 20 percent for 2009.
The second-quarter feat is a team record.
Having spent more time in the Jets uniform than anyone else in the last eight-plus seasons, defensive back Shaun Ellis thought he'd seen it all.
Then he watched Sunday's second quarter play out, as the Jets turned a scoreless game into a comeback.
"Never seen anything like it", said Ellis.
The second quarter began after the Jets and Arizona Cardinals had equaled the grey of the threatening clouds above them with a flickering play.
Then quarterback Brett Favre found Laveranues Coles for a 12-yard touchdown, providing the perfect signal for an afternoon in which their rising tune took a giant leap forward.
Favre found Coles for two more touchdowns in the fourth quarter, including one when a cornerback went down and another with 10 seconds left at the end of the first half.
"I didn't go off my path", Favre said of all the steps that came to Coles.
He's a great player.
Our communication was great, despite what people may think".
As Favre and Coles played catch, the defense was hitting hard at Cardinals quarterback Kurt Warner.
Cornerback Darrelle Revis intercepted a walk and returned it for 32 yards on a touchdown.
Security Eric Smith anticipated another pass and intercepted it.
Linebacker David Bowens has a fumble by Warner.
The final turnover, Bowens' forced fumble, may have been the most remarkable.
The Cardinals took the lead on that possession with 10 seconds left, and after the Jets had taken the ball with 10 minutes left, Jay Feely kicked a 20-yard field goal, for a 34-to-nothing lead.
That's more than the Jets have ever scored in a quarter.
When asked to describe the madness, Jets coach Eric Mangini said, "The second quarter or the third quarter?"
When he was told both - the Jets gave up 21 unanswered points in the third quarter - Mangini said, "I can tell you that I liked the second quarter much more than the third".
There were a lot of stitches in a short amount of time".
Gebrselassie rested to break his own world record
Haile Gebrselassie of Ethiopia has shown again why many consider him the greatest marathon runner of all time, breaking his own world record at the Berlin Marathon on Sunday and becoming the first person to run a 26.2 mile race in under 2 hours and 4 minutes.
With a victory in the favourably flat race in 2:03:59, Gebrselassie shatters his previous record of 2:03:26 run last year in Berlin by 27 seconds.
At 35, Gebrselassie sets the 26th world record in a career so amazing that it has produced a world champion or a world record at every distance from the metric mile to the marathon.
Last month, Gebrselassie skipped the Beijing Olympic marathon, fearing - perhaps too alarmingly, in retrospect - that air pollution would worsen his asthma problems.
Instead, he decided to run to Berlin.
In almost perfect conditions - sunny and 48 degrees at the start, 55 degrees at the finish - Gebrselassie won on Sunday with a scorching average of 4 minutes and 43 seconds per mile.
As soon as half-marathoners like Gebrselassie and Paul Tergat of Kenya went to the long distances, the marathon record has fallen by more than two minutes in the past decade, since Ronaldo from Costa del Brazil won in Berlin in 2:06:05 in 1998.
After Sunday's victory, Gebrselassie told reporters that two weeks ago he had cramps in his calves and missed a week of training.
Clearly, rest left him fresh, not rusty.
"I am so happy", Gebrselassie told reporters, adding that he was "very happy".
"Everything was perfect.
I started again a week ago, and I had some doubts today, but in the end everything went well".
He has been criticized a bit - especially in Kenya, Ethiopia's East African rival - for over-orchestrating his races, generally avoiding many of the world's top marathon stars, relying on the open-track as if it were a half-marathon race, and putting world records above the sense of competition.
But these criticisms rarely diminish the greatness of Gebrselassie's skills as a marathon runner.
With the pace of four Kenyan cyclists on Sunday, Gebrselassie reached the halfway point in 1:02:04.
Two elite Kenyan runners, James Kwambai and Charles Kamathi, held Gebrselassie in competition after the openers vanished.
With just over three miles to go, Gebrselassie made a final upset to separate from Kwambai, who finished second in 2:05:36, improving his personal best by almost 5 minutes.
Kamathi came third in 2:07:48.
In the women's race, Irina Mikitenko, a native of Kazakhstan who is now a German citizen, completed a remarkable year by winning in 2:19:19, the seventh fastest time ever.
Paula Radcliffe of Great Britain holds the world record with a time of 2:15:25.
Last spring, Mikitenko, 36, was a surprise winner of the London Marathon in 2:24:14.
She missed the Beijing Games with what is being described as a bad crash, but recovered to win in Berlin, setting her personal best time of almost five minutes in the third marathon she ran.
She ran a race that she did well, letting a quartet of Ethiopian and Kenyan runners start with a big gap, catching them up after about 18 and a half miles.
Askale Tafa Magarsa of Ethiopia finished second in 2:21.31, while Helena Kiprop of Kenya finished third in 2:25:01.
In a city apart, pride and processes of a black life
Tucked away in the sprawling theme park on the outskirts of Orlando, just a few miles from the glitz, the noise, the enormity, lies the quiet city where the pride and the complications of the African-American experience come to life.
Eatonville, the first all-black incorporated town in the country and the birthplace of Zora Neale Hurston, is no longer as simple as she described it in 1935: "the town of five lakes, three croquet fields, 300 brown skins, 300 good swimmers, plenty of guava, two schools and no jail".
It's a place of pilgrimage now.
Alice Walker, Toni Morrison and Ruby Dee came to the annual Zora! Festival in Eatonville to pay their respects to Hurston, the most famous writer of the Harlem Renaissance.
Yet in many ways, the town he described - and which makes tourists stop by including it in the Depression-era Federal Writers' Project's Florida tourist guide - remains a place apart.
It is as independent, dignified, and private as it was in the 1930s, when Hurston wrote that rural blacks in Florida often resisted sharing their thoughts with the white man, who "knowing so little of us, does not know what he is missing".
Even now, in a year where a black presidential nominee, Senator Barack Obama, has been called to a keynote address on race, many here remain wary of the outsider's gaze.
"We are very careful about how our story is told", said Hortense Jones, 59, a lifelong resident and member of the city's oldest church.
"It must be right".
Eatonville has long been defined as a paradox of triumph and difficulty.
It's both a historic model of black power grab and a community of nearly 2,400 where the poverty rate is twice the national average.
It is a literary center but also a shadowy example of the rural black culture of the South - sometimes disdained, sometimes rewarded - born from American slavery.
Not surprisingly, the residents here are both proud and protective.
And the concern for the image of Eatonville really started with Zora, who everyone here calls Hurston.
She introduced the world to her hometown through sincere, dialect-rich books, such as "Mules and Men" (1935) and "Their Eyes Were Watching God" (1937).
Five paragraphs of the Florida Guide transformed the town, just off Route 17, a road that runs through the often forgotten heart of Florida into a setting of black history and human drama.
A low-life and literary titan, Hurston took readers to the store owned by Eatonville's first mayor, Joe Clarke, and then diverted them to more private areas.
"Off the road to the left", he wrote, "is the modern public school, brown with white trim, with its well-kept and courtyards gardens, which Howard Miller always looked after, thinking he could hardly read and write".
She also mentioned the widow Dash's new husband and wrote that Lee Glenn "sells all kinds of drinks and anything that fits in the passing rooms".
So in just a few hundred words, Hurston connected Eatonville with self-government but also with illiteracy, second marriages and sex.
Clearly this wasn't Fodor's.
In fact, it was not a portrait that everyone appreciated.
"Zora said it like it was", said Ella Dinkins, 90, one of the Johnson girls who Hurston immortalised, quoting men singing coarse songs about their beauty.
He adds: "Some people don't like it".
Hurston is still remembered here as a vivacious eccentric who frequently returned from her family's relocation to Jacksonville, Fla.
Augustus Franklin, 77, recalls that when Hurston was in town, he would arrive unannounced in a triumphant Chevrolt, smoking and wearing pants in a city that still boasts dignified attire.
Many residents were fascinated, Mr. Franklin says, while others were puzzled.
"People were always very glad to see Zora", said Mr. Franklin.
But, he added, rocking in his chair on the back patio overlooking Lake Sabelia, where Hurston was most likely baptized, "he never stayed long".
When Hurston died in 1960, she was poor and her books were out of print.
Along with the rest of the world, Eatonville seemed to have forgotten her.
Although she was once a literary star, a contemporary of Langston Hughes and the only black woman at Barnard College in the 1920s, she was buried in an unmarked grave in Fort Pierce, Fla., where she had lived.
In Eatonville, there were no big memorial services, and no big conference.
"I don't think they understand his contribution to the world or his legacy to everyone", said Valerie Boyd, author of "Wrapped in Rainbows", a biography of Hurston published in 2003.
A change took place in the 1980's.
Orange County officials wanted to lay a five-lane freeway across the city to replace Kennedy Boulevard, the main two-lane road.
Orlando's expansion has already pushed Interstate 4 across the western edge of the city.
The proposal came at a time when Eatonville was still recovering from a difficult period in its history.
Forced integration, among other things, had ended the relative idyll of the community's isolation.
In the 1950's, the battle over racial mixing brought hatred to the doorstep of the community.
"During that time, a group of white boys came and threw oranges and things at the people sitting on the side", says Mr. Franklin.
"We actually had a girl killed by that one time.
They threw a watermelon out of a car".
In a 1955 letter to The Orlando Sentinel, Hurston petitioned the Supreme Court for forced integration, calling his decision in Brown v. Board of Education "an insult rather than an honor to my race".
Residents now say that desegregation of the schools, while positive in some ways, is diluting Eatonville's cohesion and jeopardizing the confidence of its young people.
"Black kids used to be hugged - I remember this - you'd hug your teacher in the morning, you'd hug your teacher in the evening", said N.Y. Nathiri, the daughter of Ella Dinkins and the executive director of Preserve the Eatonville Community, a nonprofit group.
This continued, he added, until the teachers and students were not from the same place.
"You didn't hug your white teacher because your white teacher... - I mean, there's a cultural divide there", said Mrs. Nathiri.
Civil rights, however, helped and created space for many other Zora Neale Hurstons - black writer, actress and artist who overcame prejudice, as she did, with cheerful self-confidence and lines like, "How can some deny themselves the pleasure of my company!
I just can't figure it out".
In 1975, writer Alice Walker began a long walk to Hurston's unmarked grave and began to fight for the resurrection of her reputation.
Five years later, an acclaimed biography of Hurston by Robert E. Hemenway hit bookstore shelves, reintroducing her to the American canon.
The highway project came just as his most famous daughter had once again turned the spotlight.
And this time, Hurston's old neighbors saw her as a savior.
The community began planning in 1988 a festival dedicated to Hurston to show what could ruin the state with its highway.
Thousands of fans came to the inaugural event two years later, and every January, many return for the commemoration.
Many years later, the state backed away from its road project.
"The five lanes of the resurrected highway, have brought what you would call high speed, a real pride for the city", Ms. Nathiri said.
Mrs. Boyd puts it more simply: "Zora saved Eatonville".
Winning on the highway project helped change the image the city has of itself.
Out-of-towners like Rachelle Munson, a lawyer who started coming to church here in 1993, started showing up in large numbers, and residents started reevaluating the past.
Eatonville was added to the National Register of Historic Places in 1998.
A new single-story bookstore (named after Hurston, of course) opened in 2006 on a newly paved and embellished Kennedy Boulevard.
Today, Eatonville remains a Florida anomaly: just six miles from downtown Orlando, it can feel like a back street in the summer rain, as small as it was when it was founded by just 27 black families in the 1880s.
(It is 90 percent black today.)
Outsiders who come to seek the history of Eatonville, for its significance, are often still treated with caution.
Prior permission is required for most interviews, but some things - like the murals on the oldest church in Eatonville, painted by a white man, showing black men in the fields - are not allowed to be photographed.
Many in Eatonville, like Ms. Jones, a chubby teacher with a weakness for bright red, still fear that their island community will be misunderstood.
Yet, as the Hurston Festival has expanded, so has a high level of civic pride.
Young people, in particular, tend to see Eatonville with Hurston seeing his entire race: beautiful, troubled and all, not better, not worse and fierce, creative, hard-working, dumb and confused like other races and ethnic groups in America.
It is sincere civic affection that can be heard in the voice of Mr. Franklin's 18-year-old nephew, Edwin Harvey, who plans to return to Eatonville after college to work in local government or for the police department, which he said might need help.
And even those who are younger, like Alondra and Alexia Kenon, 11-year-old twins from Winter Park, seem to have learned to describe Eatonville correctly.
"Many people, if they just got here, will think, 'Oh, this town is nothing compared to all the others,'" said Alondra Kenon after a recent Sunday service.
"But if you really stop and take a moment to look at the history, it's a really pretty city".
Here in New York, we all speak fluently of finance.
On the surface, nothing has changed.
If tourists in Manhattan stayed away from the newsstands and the giant TV screens in Times Square, they would not realize that they were in the eye of the hurricane.
They would never guess that the glass offices, nestled high above their heads the bankers and hedge fund managers who monopolise New York live every day the worst "bad day in the office" since the 1929 crash.
The porters shake metal tea carts across the sidewalks, carrying trays of muffins for the breakfast meetings.
Hispanics drag their feet between apartment blocks carrying, like human mules, 50 broken, straightened shirts hanging from a stick on their shoulders.
Employees still queue for their morning bagel at the food carts on the sidewalks, and it's still impossible to get a yellow taxi between 4 and 7 p.m. on a workday.
There didn't seem to be a real crisis, until, with all the talk of ruin and sadness, I decided to open a new savings book on Thursday afternoon.
Although I had planned the affair to coincide with the late afternoon break at my JP Morgan Chase branch, a queue of about twenty was already waiting in line.
Not in front of the cashier's desk, to withdraw money or make deposits, but in front of the customer service desk, where old customers order checkbooks, tourists ask directions to Macy's department store and new customers open accounts.
Many of those in front of me, I would later learn from Starr, my "trusted banker", were in line for the same reason.
Unlike me, however, they have already taken the savings from the smaller banks in the places where the commuters are located, such as those in New Jersey, Pennsylvania and Staten Island.
They have taken money from so-called thrift (a bit like a construction company), credit unions and types of community savings banks whose branches operate only within a state, and they say they treat customers like family.
In the past few years, 15 of these banks have failed.
In the past few days, Washington Mutual, a bank with $327 billion in assets, has been placed under supervisory administration, and as New Yorkers headed home for the weekend on a Friday afternoon, another bank, Wachovia, with $440 billion in savings deposits, was looking for a buyer to bail it out.
The employees and customers in front of me, terrified of another collapse, were moving their money to a bank perceived as a safe haven, the bank that is asking for more Wall Street collateral.
In recent weeks, ordinary New Yorkers have become proficient in finance.
A woman at my trusted Chinese supermarket, talking on the phone, referred to Lehman Brothers, the failed bank, and its emaciated general manager Dick Fuld in all familiarity, as if complaining about a lazy colleague.
And, Lyn, the uniformed janitor, nearly 50 years old from my apartment building, has changed the subject from our usual topic of conversation about Brad and Angelina or my grocery delivery.
She told me, after my visit to the bank, "Now I have all my savings in market funds!
I'm not taking any chances".
Muslim graves desecrated as Austria turns to the right.
Heinz-Christian Strache, left of the Austrian right wing of the Freedom Party and Filip Dewinter of the Belgian right wing Vlaams Belang, take part in a demonstration to introduce the organization "Cities against Islamization" in Antwerp, Thursday, January 17, 2008.
They carry signs like those on the street representing mosques with a red line running through the middle.
Police blamed right-wing extremists for desecrating a Muslim cemetery in Austria, the same week that far-right political parties gained a lot in the national general election.
More than 90 graves were severely damaged at the Traun cemetery near Linz in the few hours between Friday night and this morning, in what police believe was an organized action.
The perpetrators spray-painted Jewish symbols such as the Star of David over some graves, but detectives believe it may have been an attempt to mask extremist motives driven by hatred for Muslim immigrants.
It is unclear whether the incident is in any way related to the election.
A spokesman for the local Islamic community said they were "deeply shocked" by the news of the desecration, which occurred near the end of Ramadan, a religious month for Muslims.
Austria, meanwhile, has embarked on a spiritual quest following its rightward turn in yesterday's parliamentary elections.
The two far-right parties that took almost 30 percent of the vote, the Freedom Party of Austria and the Alliance for the Future of Austria, campaigned with strongly anti-immigration ticket tickets and some of their slogans were defined by xenophobic critics.
Heinz-Christian Strache, the leader of the Freedom Party who won over 18 percent of the vote, has campaigned against veils and burkas and has also expressed his opposition to foods that are perceived as being connected to Islam.
At the final rally in Vienna, he spoke of a "European brotherhood" to prevent the growth of Islam.
Both parties seem to ban the construction of mosques and minarets, arguing that they are political symbols of a continuing Islamization of Austria and Europe.
Polls and analyses conducted immediately after the election established the far right as the strongest political bloc in the nation, indicating that change was predominantly being brought about by young voters who are concerned about their future in the European Union.
Foreign travel banned for Gary Glitter.
Gary Glitter, the glam rock star guilty of child sexual abuse, has been banned from traveling to France and Spain by the court.
Magistrates imposed a six-month ban on Glitter after he informed the authorities monitoring him that he wanted to go to Spain via France.
The Kent Police were granted the travel ban last Thursday after they provided evidence to magistrates of Glitter's previous arrests for sexual abuse of minors.
Glitter, whose real name is Paul Gadi, was not present at the hearing at the Ashford Crown Court in Kent but was represented by the lawyers of Corker Binning.
A spokesman for the Court Service said: "On Thursday 25 September at Ashford Crown Court, Kent Police lodged a request to prevent Mr Paul Gadd from travelling abroad to France and Spain until 25 March.
"Paul Gadd was not present in person".
Glitter, 64, had informed authorities that he intended to travel abroad as required by the sex offender registry.
He must give notice to the authorities if he wishes to travel abroad for more than three days.
He is also required to give the police seven days' notice of his scheduled departure date.
Failure to notify the authority may lead to a sentence of up to five years in prison.
Kent police have said they don't want to discuss individual cases or Glitter's possible movements in the country.
A Kent Police spokesman said: "Kent Police will do whatever is necessary to protect children in this country or abroad.
"It is easier, in our view, to monitor someone who remains in the UK because we have adequate comprehensive systems in place to manage any potential risk more effectively.
"Protecting Kent residents is the primary concern of the Kent Police and we work closely to monitor the behaviour of convicted sex offenders across the country to minimise any potential risk to the public.
Glitter returned to the UK last month after serving 27 months in a Vietnamese prison for molesting two girls aged 10 and 11.
When Glitter came, he flew to Bangkok where he was supposed to board a flight to London.
But he said he was feeling ill and refused to fly to London.
Thai authorities would not let him pass passport control and he eventually took a flight to Hong Kong.
Chinese authorities also refused to let him in and he returned to Bangkok where Thai police and immigration officials insisted that he return to England.
He eventually arrived at Heathrow Terminal 3 on 22 August and stayed there while his lawyer David Corker went to the police station in Uxbridge, west London, as Scotland Yard had successfully applied for an order to place him on the sex offenders' register.
Glitter had previously been jailed in the UK in 1999 for possessing child abuse images.
A Home Office source said that Jacqui Smith, the Home Secretary, felt reassured and happy that Glitter had been stopped from travelling to France and Spain.
"I photograph the master away from the scene to extract the character" Günther Bauer, photographer
No heels, no flyers, no clothes from before.
Only the essence of the great masters of flamenco, stripped of the concentration that characterizes the performance, to look at the relaxed appearance of the man or woman.
On one side, the artist.
On the other, the person.
Two faces that are inseparable, except in private, in those moments far from the audience, when the intimacy of a gesture, the depth of a stolen look or the expressiveness of the hands, are natural because they don't have to go on stage.
The German Günther Bauer in "Flamenco-People" alternates the theatricality of some shots to singers, dancers and guitarists on the stage with the lesser known side of these masters.
With this lens, the photographer offers an original iconography of flamenco, capturing it from different visual angles.
The exhibition, included in the program of the Month of Flamenco Photography, reflects the international importance of this dance, which is growing every day", explains the artist and clarifies that in "Flamenco-People" it could also be about ordinary people, but seeing the photos, the observer realizes that they are not the typical images of artists, performers or performers on the scene.
These people portrayed "on the street" are "artists who are able to convey passion, sadness, joy when they are on stage ... and to capture the audience.
To capture the personality of these great men, it is not necessary to portray them on stage,
Because their personality and character is internal.
What I was interested in was creating an intimate atmosphere that would allow me to capture with the camera the personality of the great flamenco players".
With a passion for the "Cante de las Minas" festival, Bauer began in 1997 a long journey to portray singers, guitarists or dancers using a plate camera.
These are portraits that, because of the type of machine and material, are reminiscent of classic photography.
The application of different stylistic techniques breaks with the traditional principles of the image, giving the photo modernity, according to an idea that reflects Bauer's own conception of flamenco: "A music with very traditional roots that evolves and is able to surprise every day".
Not the dancing, the singing or the playing itself, but the personality of the artist, his character, capable of winning over the audience with his art.
The search for an encounter with the essential elements, with the magic that becomes visible in a certain way of feeling and of being, are and have been the constant of this work, on display these days at the gallery El Fotómata.
Famous flamenco artists such as Diego El Cigala, Chano Lobato, Cristina Hoyos, Enrique Morente, El Lebrijano, Antonio Canales, Vicente Amigo, among others, are included in this selection of about seventy portraits by artists.
The project has become a sort of anthology of flamenco, and will soon be published in a book that will collect the portraits exhibited on the occasion of the exhibition.
The passion for portraits led Bauer to repeat the idea two years ago with "Portraits of veteran athletes" ("SportARTproject").
Although in "Flamenco-People" the concept is different, the photographer admits "I love to portray people, to get to know them and to be able to penetrate for a moment into their life, whether this is a long or short moment.
I think portraiture is the hardest genre in photography.
You meet or confront people, characters that you sometimes don't even know or who only allow you a few minutes to take the picture.
Beyond these circumstances, as a photographer, I always try to make my ideas concrete".
The collection of contemporary flamenco portraits, entitled "Flamenco-people" is set up at the El Fotómata gallery, at number 20 of the Via de la Mata, parallel to the Via Alameda de Hercules, and will be open to the public until next October 16.
Vargas Llosa reveals that the novel he is writing is a "chance"
It is set in places he still does not know and deals with unknown subjects: despite this, Mario Vargas Llosa is struggling with a new project he is working on, a novel whose protagonist, Roger Casemant, is an Irish nationalist who has lived twenty years in Congo and crossed the Amazon.
The writer, who has always been a favorite for the Nobel Prize for Literature, confessed yesterday at the Hay Festival in Segovia that the project he is working on today "is a gamble" and that "everything indicates that I shouldn't write it".
"If I had any sense, I wouldn't write it, but I will do it anyway and I hope to finish it as soon as possible", he concluded his speech at the festival for the exchange of ideas, thoughts and words that for four days saw a hundred writers, historians, journalists and thousands of people pass through the city of the Aqueduct.
The author of "La ciudad y los perros" was, as expected, the leading figure at the third edition of the festival of the word.
Vargas Llosa, who won the Hay Festival award for being the writer most voted by the participants  an antique edition of Dickens' book "Our mutual friend", filled the seats at the Juan Bravo theater.
Presented by Félix Romeo, the writer found himself in front of an audience to whom time has flown when the Peruvian, with a prodigious memory and with great doses of humor, has recalled how he was born in him the literary vocation, derived from the "extraordinary adventure" of the "pleasure of reading" and "to live beyond what I lived"; how he writes in "disciplined mode" to supplement the "lack of inspiration", with an intense work of documentation, editing and continuous re-making; how Faulkner, Victor Hugo and Alexandre Dumas have influenced his vocation and how "the images of memory" are the basis on which his stories are based.
The Spanish-American novelist, has acknowledged that "there is no way" to measure and know if books can change people's lives, "but I refuse to believe that literature is a pure entertainment, an ephemeral experience", Vargas Llosa stressed, arguing that, on the contrary, "it has effects" and that "makes people more non-conformist".
Weather is hampering the Pozoblanco Festival, depriving it of bullfighting
The celebration of the bullfights that were supposed to seal the days of the Festival of Pozoblanco was suspended yesterday morning, after the bullfighters selected for the bullfights had verified that the ground conditions of the square were not adequate.
Therefore, the company, in agreement with Fermin Bohorquez, Pablo Hermoso de Mendoza and Leonardo Hernandez, decided to suspend the celebration of the bullfight.
The weather has been so bad that two out of three days of the festival have been lost.
On Saturday, rain prevented the second running of the bulls.
In the picture were Jose Luis Moreno, Curro Diaz and Juan Bautista, who would have to face a bull of Castilblanco.
Therefore, the Festival was held regularly only on Fridays.
On this occasion it was Daniel Luque who triumphed, cutting off three ears and being brought out in triumph, after having bullfighted with taste and aesthetics.
That same afternoon, Alejandro Talavante completed his two races, receiving a salute and an ear, granted more by the audience than by the race itself.
The worst of all was El Juli, passing through the arena of Los Llanos without glory and without pain.
With the second bull, after a tremendous muleta, he earned the whistles of a large part of the audience.
A truck with 2,000 kilos of hashish passes the checkpoint in Alava
It's five minutes to ten in the morning.
Officers alert two occupants of a van who, instead of stopping, run away.
Officers alerted the two occupants of a van who, instead of stopping, ran away.
Their cargo, over two tons of hashish, is a good reason not to stop.
The officers chased them down and arrested one of the occupants, a 28-year-old man identified as A.A.J., according to a statement from the Basque government's Interior Ministry.
The individual arrested is charged with drug trafficking and falsification of public documents.
The accident occurred when some road officials from Alava were carrying out a traffic check on the N-1, at the point where it crosses the municipal district of Armiñón.
They were about to stop a van for inspection when the driver, in defiance of orders, suddenly accelerated and overtook the checkpoint.
The officers pursued the vehicle until it stopped on the side of the road after a couple of kilometers, and the two occupants fled into a wooded area.
Erzaintza agents were able to arrest one of the fugitives and to seize the 2,178 kilograms of hashish they were transporting and they noted once they inspected the van, an Iveco Daily.
The hashish bags, which were found in the back of the vehicle, were subsequently taken into police custody for further investigation and weight tracking.
Furthermore, since officials found that the number plate had been "duplicated" because it did not match the one shown on the van's registration papers, the arrested man was also charged with the offense of falsifying public documents.
Ertzaintza is continuing the investigation to arrest the second suspect, who managed to escape as mentioned, and to determine the origin of the seized drugs.
The prisoner A. A. J., 28 years old, was taken to the police station to carry out the necessary procedures and to be at the disposal of the judge in the next few hours.
Actress Heather Locklear arrested for driving under the influence of drugs
Actress Heather Locklear, Amanda from the popular TV series Melrose Place, was arrested this weekend in Santa Barbara, California, for driving under the influence of drugs.
A witness saw her performing a risky maneuver while trying to drive her car out of the parking lot at Montecito, a spokesman for the California Highway Patrol told People magazine.
The witness stated that at about 4:30 p.m. Locklear "was slamming the gas pedal, making a lot of noise, and trying to get the car out of the parking lot with abrupt back and forth manoeuvres, backing up, passing several times in front of her sunglasses".
Shortly after, the witness, who at first glance did not seem to recognize the actress, saw Locklear pull up on a nearby road and exit the vehicle.
It was this person who alerted the emergency services because "she was concerned for Locklear's life".
When the police patrol arrived, they found the actress sitting inside her vehicle, which was partially blocking the road.
"She seemed confused", and that's why the officers took her to a drug and alcohol-use facility to have her tested.
According to a police spokesman, the actress has been cooperative and the alcohol problem has been ruled out from the start, although "according to what the officers observed at first, we believe Locklear was under the influence of some drug".
Locklear was arrested on suspicion of driving under the influence of some unspecified substance and was locked up in the local jail around 7 p.m., to be released a few hours later.
Two months ago, Locklear was released and rehabilitated from a specialty clinic in Arizona after being hospitalized following an episode of anxiety and depression.
