"Sangre de mayo", the epic wager made by Garcia
Inspired by Episodios Nacionales by Benito Pérez Galdós, Jose Luis Garci re-proposes in Sangre de mayo the famous revolt of the Spaniards against the French, in what is the most ambitious film of his filmography, with almost 15 million euros of budget.
With this film, the director has tried to "illustrate the torrent of characters and at the same time the social analysis" that he has always admired in the work of the famous novelist, he explained today during the presentation of the film, with Quim Gutierrez and Paula Echevarría at the head of a large cast of interpreters.
Sangre de mayo, more than two and a half hours long, debuts this Friday in theaters, to become a future TV miniseries of more than four hours on TeleMadrid.
A great admirer of Galdós's literature, Jose Luis Garci claims to have realized "a childhood dream" with this film, and feels he should thank Esperanza Aguirre, who was commissioned by the Community of Madrid three years before to shoot a commemorative film for the second centenary of 2 May medrilegno. The director had accepted on condition that the story was based on the novel Episodios Nacionales.
The 15 million budget, all of which was provided by the Community of Madrid, represented a "unique opportunity" for Garci to recreate the scenery and costumes to portray "a stunned Spain that had the wrong leader to fight for and the fact that the struggle for independence brought the people a huge developmental delay under the reign of Ferdinand VII", Garci noted.
However, the director regrets not having received funding equal to those of Alatriste or Los fantasmas de Goya - more than twice that of Sangre de mayo, for which it was not possible to shoot some scenes provided for by the scenography that he himself had signed together with Horacio Valcarcel, a collaborator of almost his entire career.
This, for the director of Volver a empezar, has influenced what is his usual work practice, the staging with the actors, with whom he often uses to rehearse before shooting together with those who will not be part of the cast, because he considers it "humiliating", considering that "part of the director's job is to go to the theater and cinema to know what is happening in the sector in which he works".
Many of the performers, some of whom are part of the cast of Sangre de mayo, rehearse in front of his car, as in the case of Michael Rell, Carlos Larranaga or Fernando Guillen Cuervo.
Four-time Oscar nominee - winning one - Garci believes that none of the three films nominated to represent Spain at the Hollywood Academy this year - his Sangre de mayo, Siete mesas de billar francés and, the last selected Los girasoles ciegos - represent the younger generation of Spanish cinema "who should instead be known".
This is not a film Garci expects awards.
"At first you think you're working for posters, then you realize you're only working for prosperity, and at some point you settle for just making one more film", explains Garci after more than 30 years in the business.
Isabel Bayon rediscovers the essence of the Spanish dancer Tortola Valencia
A dancer from Seville pays tribute to another dancer from Seville.
Carmen Valencia Tortola, Catalan father (Firenze Tortola Ferrer) and Andalusian mother (Georgina Valencia Valenzuela), was born in the Triana district, and at the age of three moved with her family to London.
She was a free-dancer and a specialist in oriental dances.
She led a fascinating life and was a pioneer of women's emancipation, the caliber of Isadora Duncan, Virginia Woolf or Sarah Bernhardt.
She was a Buddhist and vegetarian, and advocated for the abolition of the corset, which prevented women from moving freely.
The life of this woman, who marked a revolution in the field of dance and aesthetics in Europe between the two wars, has always fascinated Isabel Bayon.
"I would have liked to work with Pepa Gamboa and she offered me this character.
The dancer maintains: "We don't claim to tell his whole life, but to capture the spirit.
The titles of his dances suggested to me some basic elements of flamenco.
So, "the dance of the butterfly" suggested a guajira, or "the dance of the snake" some tanghi.
Her dancing was sensual and I was told that my dancing was part of this aesthetic", she explains.
The staging includes two exceptional contributions: that of Miguel Poveda, who will sing Isabel again in one of his shows, as he does in "La puerta abierta"; and that of the teacher Matilde Coral, who exceptionally wanted to work with what had been a pupil of hers.
"Matilde plays Tortola as an adult, the character of maturity.
I am happy that he has agreed to work in my opera and I feel very honoured by this".
The set also includes the musical composition and guitarists like Jesus Torres and Paco Arriaga, the singing of Miguel Ortega, the Pulga y Moi by Morón; the percussion of El Pájaro, as well as the viola of Rafa La Viola and the collaboration of an actor, Juanfran Juárez "who plays the role of eternal accompanist of these artists who have been dives all round, and who have always had many entertainers".
The opera also presents in some form the life of this woman who takes place in faraway places, especially for that time, such as India, the United States or Russia, and then all over Europe, since, habitually, she resided in London.
"I wanted to remember her because I think she is one of the women who had a huge influence in a given historical period and now no one remembers her and even less considers her work as something of value", says Bayon.
The show will begin today at 8:30 at the Lope de Vega theater.
The publication of the Diario de un poeta recién casado also marks the end of the Triennium
The presentation of the first illustrated edition of the "Diario de un Poeta Reciencasado" at the church of Saint Stephen (New York), where Juan Ramón Jiménez married Zenobia in March 1916, is part of the activities planned by the Cultural Advisory of the Andalusian Government to celebrate the "Triennio de Zenobia y Juan Ramon" (2006-2008), organized to commemorate the fiftieth anniversary of the award of the Nobel Prize for literature and the death of both.
The "Triennium of Zenobia and Juan Ramon" thus concludes with the re-edition of this work, with the International Congress held in New York, with the restoration of the Nobel's house-museum and with the travelling exhibition "Juan Ramón Jiménez: Aquel chopo de luz", which was inaugurated last May and which, after having visited the various provinces of Andalusia, is expected to arrive in New York at the same time as the International Congress.
In addition, the Cultural Office of the Junta of Andalusia has acquired a total of eight hundred copies of the "Diary of a Reciencasado Poet", edited by Pietro Tabernero and illustrated by James Perez-Enciso, to continue the dissemination of the figure and work of one of the Andalusian poets of highest value.
