Microsoft is looking for a virtual receptionist.
At the MIT Emerging Technologies Conference, Microsoft previewed a new image recognition and human interaction system, a kind of artificial intelligence, but without much intelligence, that can perform some basic tasks, like hailing a taxi (or, in Microsoft's case, a shuttle service to get around the company campus) by assisting the phone user.
Using a camera and a face and shape recognition system, this receptionist is able to know how many people are in a room, who they are - including remembering their position in the company - and to listen and understand the key words in a conversation with them.
It can also group those in attendance into conversation groups.
In the example video, the receptionist notices a third person, but she understands that he is not from the group she is talking to and that he is not an employee of the company.
He asks if she's there to visit someone and tells her he'll be available shortly.
All without the blue screen.
That's very impressive.
But this, of course, is the future.
Now the company has better things to focus on, like the next version of its Windows operating system.
There's been a lot of talk this week about a change of strategy at Microsoft.
Windows 7 will be lighter and will not have many associated programs.
Steve Ballmer found that if computers were equipped with the essential functions and less loaded with commercial junk, they would run five times faster.
Quite a breakthrough, considering that Microsoft, version after version, has continually added features and "extras" to Windows.
The change of direction is appreciable.
Microsoft is right: the operating system is becoming less important, and with it the software.
When Google launched Chrome on the web, I was one of those who argued that it was Google's first step to compete with Windows.
Many rightly point out that a browser is not an operating system.
The operating system will always be necessary because it is a vital element for the hardware and software to communicate.
It serves the same function as your wife or husband when you have something to say to your mother-in-law.
That's right.
It will never go away, but perhaps we need to think of the "death" of the operating system not as an absolute truth, but as a relative one.
What Ballmer said this week confirms that idea.
People are paying less and less attention to the operating system, and more and more to the Web browser.
You pick up your computer just to launch Explorer or Firefox -- or Chrome -- and every day we spend more time browsing the web than in a remote, window-based environment.
What are half the applications in the operating system for?
Less is more.
And Windows 7 has to be less, much less than Vista.
Less heavy, less overloaded, less complex.
Microsoft is interested in integrating its own online services more to make them a viable alternative to Google.
They are in desperate need of it, in fact, and I'll give you a little example.
I took the photograph included in this post at one of Microsoft's Redmond employee rec room earlier this month.
On the soda machine, a sign urges them to use their own search tool - "Your Search. Our Future".
In 2006, an independent study concluded that 66% of Microsoft employees use Google to conduct a web search.
