Alcoholic drivers will have to install the "alcolock"
The Ministry of Interior requires that drivers with three administrative sanctions for excessive blood alcohol levels, install in your car the system that prevents the vehicle from driving in a state of intoxication or if you do not blow in the appropriate device.
The measure was announced last June and is already included in the annual report of the State Attorney General, according to which it will be a pilot project lasting one year.
The aim of this project is to reintegrate the driver, since he will have to attend a rehabilitation course on the road.
In addition to the General Prosecutor's Office for Road Safety, the Directorate-General for Traffic (DGT) and the Technological Institute for Automotive Safety Foundation (FITSA) will be involved in this initiative.
According to statistics, between 30 and 75 percent of drivers who are reported more than once for drunk driving then drive their car again.
Alcohollock would avoid this, because it is a system attached to the vehicle that measures the alcohol content of exhaled air and prevents the car from starting if the driver does not blow, or when a higher than permitted alcohol concentration is detected.
The cost is more than 1000 euros and would be borne by the convicted.
In this regard, a study carried out in the United States in 2007 showed that vehicles equipped with such devices reduce the number of infringements by up to 65% during the first year of introduction.
And in Spain it is estimated that it could save the lives of 115 people a year.
The measure is limited to administrative sanctions for two reasons: to curb such behaviour before it becomes a criminal offence.
And to facilitate its development, since legal reform can be carried out by ordinary means, and, no doubt, the reform necessary for criminal procedure would require an organic law.
However, the device is not yet available on the Spanish market in any commercial solution, although it has already been introduced experimentally in some industrial and public vehicles.
The Congress of Deputies will vote tomorrow on an initiative by the PSOE to install this system in school buses, as has already been done in France.
