Talking in your sleep
Some babies talk in the night.
I am not talking about those who wake up very excited to tell us something that happened to them the previous day, but those children who talk while they are asleep.
The first time it happens, you're scared, but it doesn't really matter.
It is a benign sleep disorder called somniloquy.
It occurs with some frequency, especially in children and adolescents.
I'm sure most of you have been told that you talk in your sleep.
This phenomenon can occur very sporadically (once in a lifetime, e.g. associated with an episode of high fever) or more regularly (every day, once a week, once a month ...), the next day the child remembers nothing.
There is no single cause that can explain this phenomenon.
Sometimes these episodes are linked to other sleep disorders such as nightmares, night terrors, night enuresis (bedwetting), or sleepwalking, but not necessarily.
As mentioned earlier, it can be associated with stages of very high fever, stress or over-excitement.
However, it is still a little studied phenomenon.
The intensity with which it appears is also extremely variable.
The person may speak in a very quiet tone of voice, with loose words, almost in a whisper, or the opposite may occur (screaming, shouting, long speeches ...).
In cases where the event is particularly intense, the child should be observed and possibly consulted by a specialist to see if there is any issue that is generating an abnormal state of anxiety as an outflow from the situation.
We have said that this is a benign alteration so there is no treatment unless it is associated with other sleep disorders that can be treated (for example, if coupled with insomnia or a stressful situation).
What can be done is to consider a series of very simple preventive measures such as:
Try not to over-excite the baby before he goes to sleep.
Offer peaceful games and avoid TV shows or series that instill fear or suggest violence.
With very nervous children who find it difficult to relax, relaxation techniques can be used to help them gain a measure of inner calm.
This will help the baby to sleep more soundly.
Once the sleepiness sets in, try to remain calm.
Remember that they are harmless to the baby and that the next day he will remember nothing of what happened.
Helpful Tips
Don't wake him up.
It's useless, because he's not aware of what's happening, and you'd interrupt his sleep.
Although he is talking, he is sleeping and therefore resting.
Remember, if he appears very anxious and the episodes occur frequently, it is best to consult a doctor or to find out what is causing such anxiety in the child.
If you understand what he is saying (which is not the most common situation), do not be tempted to question him for information.
You'll get nothing, because he's asleep and therefore unconscious to organize his thoughts.
In addition, you are able to hear what he says but not to see what he is dreaming to say, so great care must be taken in interpreting the information and the conclusions it might lead to.
Never tell the child that you may ask questions during the night to learn his secrets.
Not even for fun.
Such a thing causes enormous anguish.
In short, don't worry, it's nothing serious, it's an episode that lasts only a few minutes.
