The meeting - the blood is safe again
Héma-Québec celebrated yesterday the tenth anniversary of its founding, and its President, Dr Francine Décary, had every reason to rejoice, as Héma-Québec has become one of the safest and most effective blood suppliers in the world.
And most importantly, it has won back the public's trust, which was badly shaken by the tainted blood scandal in the 1980s and 1990s.
As we know, the national blood supply operated by the Canadian Red Cross Transfusion Service was infected with the acquired immunodeficiency virus (HIV) and hepatitis C in the 1980's.
In the face of such a tragedy and the protests of the population, the Government of Canada conducted a public inquiry in February 1994, headed by Justice Horace Krever, which aimed to shed light on the circumstances that led to such a tragedy and to disseminate recommendations to prevent a similar disaster from happening again.
While Judge Krever was slow to draw up a report, some provinces formed a committee to devise a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, this mandate was carried out by the Gélineau Committee.
Following the Gélineau et Krever reports, two suppliers were created in Canada: Héma-Québec to supply Québec and Société canadienne du sang (Canadian Blood Society) for all other provinces and the two territories.
In 1998, when Héma-Québec started its activities, only 38% of people said they still had confidence in the donation system in Québec, recalls Dr. Décary.
It was a mortifying situation.
Thanks to continuous efforts to improve the safety of blood samples and field research over the next few years, we have regained public trust", she explains before proudly stating that by the beginning of 2008, about 94% of the Quebec population had trusted Héma-Québec.
However, Dr. Décary is convinced that "trust is an extremely fragile thing".
Since its creation on 28 September 1998, Héma-Québec has applied the precautionary principle.
At the time, there were numerous cases of the human variant of mad cow disease in Europe, a new manifestation of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, says the woman who has been its president since 1998, the year of its foundation.
"And we had no idea that the disease could be transmitted through infected blood.
It is therefore based on one of the main recommendations of the Krever and Gélinau reports, namely that when there is doubt and a serious illness could follow, in this case Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which manifests itself in a degeneration of the brain that inevitably leads to death, exclusion measures are taken.
In April 1999, blood was rejected from those who had spent more than a month in the United Kingdom since 1980.
Now, for some years, it has been proved beyond doubt that this disease is transmitted by infected blood.
This incident has thus shown us that it made sense to apply the precautionary principle".
In 1999, a much more efficient technique for detecting HIV appeared on the market: nucleic acid tests (TANs), which allow the presence of the virus to be detected directly in the blood of donors, rather than the presence of antibodies against it, on which the tests used up to then were based.
TANs have allowed the window period to be shortened, from the time the person contracted the disease to the time when the first viruses can be detected in the blood thanks to our techniques, the specialist explains.
It was possible to reduce that period to less than a week.
The risk of ignoring the presence of infected donors and thus not being able to detect them has thus been greatly reduced.
These improvements have greatly reduced the risk of contracting AIDS from a blood transfusion.
Today, one in 12 million people is at risk of receiving blood contaminated with the HIV virus.
"In other words, it would take 12 million blood samples to be distributed before anyone could be infected with the HIV virus.
Since Héma-Québec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood samples each year, it will take more than 24 years before a case of HIV transmitted by transfusion is detected.
I think that today people can feel safe to receive or prescribe a blood transfusion to restore their health, says the head of the Héma-Québec branch.
"Our challenge for the next decade is to maintain the safety of our products.
You never know which pathogen is going to emerge in the system.
The Chikungunya virus, which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted in the blood by an insect, appeared on Reunion Island just over a year ago.
We must be constantly vigilant", continues Dr. Décary, before stressing that, in addition to having safe resources, Héma-Québec must also ensure that it has enough.
"Needs are increasing as the population ages.
Since cancer treatments are more aggressive, patients often need a supply of red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing population also has consequences for the number of donors, which on average is only 3% of the inhabitants of Quebec acceptable as donors. "
However, all healthy persons over 18 years of age who meet the eligibility criteria can donate blood every 56 days, or six times a year.
On average, 14 percent of people who volunteer to donate are turned down because they have AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they've traveled to a country where AIDS is widespread, they'll be turned away for a year.
"With this 3% we can maintain an inventory capable of responding to the needs of hospitals.
Cases of shortage are very rare.
But the members of this group of donors must be renewed as they grow older and can no longer make donations.
Now it's hard to convince people to donate blood, but especially to hold them back and encourage them to become regular donors.
Life is so hectic these days that it is hard to find an hour to donate blood", says Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Héma-Québec not only distributes blood samples, but also human tissue, including bone grafts, heart valves, eyeballs and skin that is used almost exclusively for severe burns.
These tissues are analyzed, processed, and frozen before being deposited at Héma-Québec, which operates the only public cord blood bank in Quebec.
In the umbilical cord, once considered a biomedical waste, there is a lot of blood rich in stem cells that can be used to treat serious diseases, such as leukemia.
"We celebrated the deposit of our thousandth cord blood sample a few weeks ago and plan to draw more than a thousand each year.
They should be proposed for transplants early next year", says Dr. Décary, who describes this cord blood draw as a very popular practice.
" Many mothers are disappointed that they cannot access it", because Héma-Québec does not have the resources to offer this complex and expensive program to all hospitals in Québec.
