Free speech - Barrick Gold's Orwellian speech
In its September 17 edition, Le Devoir published a letter from M. Patrick J. Garver, executive vice-president of the Canadian mining company Barrick Gold.
Pursuing Orwellian logic, the latter claims that the world's largest gold company has filed a six million defamation suit against three authors and a small, penniless publishing house with the intention of initiating a "transparent public debate".
While it is true that judges are independent and impartial, it is not the truth that they judge, especially in the case of a libel suit, but the law.
Unsurprisingly, this substantial difference is completely hidden from Garver.
Because for Barrick Gold, the best way to conduct a public debate would be to ruin anyone who dares to take a position contrary to its own.
No matter the outcome of the trial, the writers and publishers of the book Canada Nero will have to spend a huge amount of money in order to organize their defense and fight, with decidedly unequal arms, against an army of lawyers financed by the practically bottomless pockets of the mining company.
Moreover, in these conflicts, the tactic is often to ruin the defendant in order to impose a consensual settlement that will muzzle the opposition as well as frighten anyone who dares to speak out again on the matter.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, it is before the public that it should have presented its view of the facts.
Contrary to what happens in many countries where Barrick Gold operates, in Canada the debate is normally held through exchanges of views and not through the use of batons.
So it would have been enough for the company to open its books, its documents, and to establish a real debate, through newspapers, media, publications and funding independent research teams that could have shed light on the issue.
But Barrick Gold does not seem to have much confidence in public opinion and has been badly rejecting petitions and letters of support for the authors of Black Canada.
Perhaps Garver could explain how he can call for a "public" debate when his contempt for that same public is so obvious?
In the world of the vice-president, it seems that this word refers exclusively to the high-paid lawyers and not to all Canadians; that is a rather narrow view of the concept.
In a democratic system, even the slanderers have a say.
What Barrack Gold doesn't understand  or doesn't want to understand  is that the public who support Canada Black's authors and publishers do so primarily because they reject the brutal methods employed by the mining company.
This audience is ready to listen to Barrick and judge, but on the basis of civil exchanges of opinion, and not in the light of what many perceive as a sort of gagging (looking for the "public debate", Barrick Gold just gave the authors of Black Canada an ultimatum telling them to suspend the use of that word...)
Beyond Garver's surreal speech, the lawsuit brought by Barrack Gold is a direct attack on the freedom of academic research and the pursuit of truth, which are indispensable in any democratic society.
It denies the right to cite authentic sources and to debate facts and interpretations, which are the very basis of intellectual work.
If in a country like Canada it is impossible to study and debate issues that are inconvenient to the world's richest corporations, and that could lead to multiple lawsuits, who can do that?
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public and transparent debate, they could do it by following scientific standards, as the authors of Black Canada do.
You have a right to reply.
For a long time, the academic environment of which we are a part has been able to handle debates and disagreements and to resolve conflicts.
The excessive measures of Barrick Gold clearly show that, contrary to its claims, it does not seek a transparent debate at all.
This is damaging to academia and to the public debate in Canada, and it is time for governments to take action to curb abusive litigation.
Operation - bailout for Wall Street  Dialogue between Republicans and Democrats
The Bush administration and congressional leaders, representing the Republican and Democratic parties, yesterday finally reached an agreement on the largest bailout since the Great Depression of the 1930s.
The new version of the $700 billion plan, which aims to put a stop to the financial crisis that has been weighing on Wall Street for months, has yet to be ratified by both houses of Congress.
It provides in particular for checks on its effective implementation by elected leaders, new mechanisms to guarantee the repayment of public money, new provisions to curb the number of houses seized for non-payment, as well as a right of inspection on the salaries paid to the managers of protected enterprises.
U.S. Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson, House Speaker Nancy Pelosi and Republican negotiator Senator Judd Gregg announced the good news a few minutes after midnight yesterday, at the end of a two-day marathon of negotiations.
"We have made great progress towards an effective agreement on markets", said Bush administration spokesman Henry Paulson.
"Every decision has been made in such a way as to safeguard the economy and the American people from the current crisis on Wall Street", the Democrat explained.
"That's the crux of it: if we hadn't acted this way, inestimable discomfort and upset would have been poured into the daily lives of Americans", Republican Judd Gregg said.
The conclusion of the negotiations was marked by concerns about the impact of a new bankruptcy on investors.
The deadline agreed corresponded to the opening of the markets this morning.
The two candidates for the US presidency, who later joined the negotiations, were quite in favour of the agreement, but did not shy away from expressing their dissatisfaction before adopting extreme solutions.
Democratic Senator Barack Obama is credited with adding some provisions to the agreement, particularly the one that will allow homeowners to keep their homes and the one concerning the salaries of state-owned business executives.
"When taxpayers are asked to take extraordinary measures because of the irresponsibility of others, there is nothing to rejoice about.
But these measures are necessary", he commented on the American TV screen.
Asked on another channel whether he would vote for the plan, his Republican opponent, John McCain, replied I would like to look into the details, but I hope so.
"From what I've read, it's something we all have to digest and that will allow us to move on".
The option of non-intervention is simply unacceptable", he said.
The $700 billion plan aims to buy back the bad loans, bad assets and unsellable assets of American financial institutions with taxpayer money.
The plan comes after 14 months of crisis due to the bursting of a real estate bubble that led first to the collapse of subprime mortgages (mortgages), then to other more widespread forms of credit securities (PCAAs) and resulted in liquidity freezing and the liquidation of banks and financial institutions.
It was a group of Republicans in office that blew up the first draft of a deal last week.
They seem to have come out of that dead end since the Democrats have accepted that the "toxic" assets of some struggling companies are only protected by the government, rather than bought.
In order to meet everyone's needs, a provision was added to the Congress that if the government were to face losses over the next five years because of this program, it could impose new taxes to maintain its balance.
The new plan provides for an initial payment of 250 billion, to which 100 billion may be added if the President deems it necessary.
The $350 billion payment would have to be ratified by another vote in Congress.
In return for its aid, Washington will get shares in the sheltered companies that will pay dividends if it makes a profit and that it can sell when the dust settles.
Under the plan, the Federal Government will be able to delay foreclosure proceedings relating to real estate loans and to set limits on the remuneration and severance pay paid to the managers of the companies involved.
Starting today, the architects of the plan would like to submit it to the vote of the House of Representatives, and to the vote of the Senate on Wednesday.
Despite all efforts, it is still not certain that their plan will be given the green light.
In fact, there were several votes against the bill yesterday, from both the Republican and Democratic parties.
"Obviously, Washington is not listening", said Republican Scott Garrett, a member of the House Finance Committee, addressing his constituents.
"Yes, we have a serious financial problem.
Yes, there are solutions.
But not to take advantage of the taxpayers.
Leader of a small congressional caucus nicknamed "the skeptics caucus", Representative Brad Sherman, a Democrat, presents the situation differently, but reaches the same conclusion.
"Four hundred eminent professors of economics, including three Nobel prize winners, have written to us to say: we ask Congress not to jump to conclusions and to examine carefully the way forward", he said yesterday.
At the same time, Europe was once again witnessing the global nature of the crisis.
After an emergency meeting, the three Benelux countries announced the partial nationalization of the Fortis banking group for EUR 11.2 billion (USD 16.3 billion).
The intervention of the governments of Belgium, the Netherlands and Luxembourg became necessary when the French bank BNS Paribas announced that it would not buy its competitor, which was in full bankruptcy after losing EUR 2 billion (USD 2.9 billion) in the subprime mortgage crisis in the United States.
Fortis has 85,000 employees and is one of the 20 largest banks in Europe and one of the 10 largest insurers.
"This is not money wasted", Dutch Finance Minister Wouter Bos said yesterday.
In return, they receive influence and voting rights in banking matters.
It is certainly something that savers and families appreciate now that times are uncertain".
At the same time, on the other side of the Channel, the British government appears to be in the process of nationalising another bank in the throes of the financial crisis.
According to the British press, the government would take over all the loans currently outstanding at Bradford and Bringley Bank, including more than $41 billion in mortgages.
The Spanish bank Santander announced yesterday that it will be buying the branches and customer accounts of the British bank.
Since the start of the economic crisis, Bradford and Bringley will be the second bank, after Northern Rock, to be nationalised by the British Government.
Paul Newman (1925-2008) - Death of a committed icon
The blue-eyed beauty was for a long time his ace in the hole, for others his weak point.
Was he free of the narcissistic mirror, the American actor with the enchanting smile?
Yes and no.
His discretion, sensitivity and obvious talent would have expelled him from that circle of powerful men devoted to true and holy monsters.
What a consistency!
Paul Newman, who died Friday at the age of 83 from lung cancer at his Connecticut ranch, remains one of the last icons of the golden age of American cinema.
Less monumental than Brando, to whom he resembled and of whom he was a sort of rival on the screen for a long time, more cautious in his game, certainly more fragile, but he also speaks for freedom and the development of dramatic beliefs.
Mixed marriages often produce magical children.
He was born in Ohio in 1925, to a German Jewish father and a mother of Hungarian descent.
From these European roots will emerge one of the glorious faces of the American dream.
A humble ego, the ultimate mark of quality.
Because in him you could recognize a whole country invaded by the safe made man, the fighter of the war of the Pacific, proud in the fight, who in the early 50s studied dramatic art at Yale, later attended the Actor Studio in New York, before triumphing in theater, television and soon in the cinema.
The same civil rights activist was also the race car driver who finished second in the 1979 24 Hours of Le Mans, and a sex symbol, though part of a model couple since 1958 with actress Joanne Woodward.
With him, the shadows of a reserved, discreet, committed star, allergic to the scandals of show business, whose mystery will never be fully revealed.
An honest man, in the noblest sense of the word.
This weekend, the passing of Paul Newman was a heartbreaking moment for moviegoers, as his great characters populate the black screen of memory.
Over half a century of American cinema in full transformation is re-proposed through his interpretations.
The memories of the charming cowboy in Butch Cassidy (1969) and the boy unable to desire his fiery wife (Elizabeth Taylor) in The Cat on the Hot Roof adapted by Tennessee Williams in 1958 are confused.
More recently, he is remembered as the sensitive Mr. Bridge (1990), troubled by a marriage that failed to deliver on its promises.
Many other Paul Newmans have passed into history.
The boxer Rocky Graziano, delinquent, tormented, violent, unforgettable in Somewhere Over There Loves Me, by Robert Wise, a role intended for James Dean and resumed after his death, which Newman officially launched in 1956.
That nice, bad-ass in the excellent Stangata, Oscar for best picture in 1973.
He was a bitter and vindictive billiards player in Lo Spaccone, a magnificent film by Robert Rossen (1961), Martin Scorsese's Il colore dei soldi, which earned him the only Oscar out of 9 nominations in 1987.
That face through the years, it was his.
It's him again.
The ages follow one another along its path.
Young people know him best for the cult film Slap Shot (1977), in which he played Reggie Dunlop, coach of an unorthodox ice hockey team.
His fans found him again in 1994 in Mr. Hula Hoop, by the Coen brothers.
The circle had closed with a final role as the godfather of the Irish mafia in It Was My Father, in 2003.
Unlike the most legendary film stars who soon abandoned the craft, Newman will remain in theaters for a long time, denouncing Hollywood in all its pomp, parties and concessions.
French film-maker Bertrand Tavernier called it, with a touch of irony, "a living challenge to underplaying", judging its performances exaggerated.
The profession wasn't always a play for the handsome Paul Newman, whose roles seemed to fall like manna from heaven.
However, he often preferred the role of the outcast to that of the young actor: neurotic, alcoholic, caragine or desperate characters, whose slop and rebellion he expressed with his perfect traits.
As a filmmaker, Newman revealed unknown shades of his true, poetic sensibility.
Jennifer's 1968 debut (based on the novel by Canadian Margaret Laurence), with wife Joanne Woodward in the title role, traced a subtle female portrait of melancholy.
He, who lost his son Scott to an overdose, dedicated in 1984 the film Harry and Son, a discreet and sad film.
Among the countless tributes paid to Newman yesterday, his great friend and former comrade-in-arms Robert Redford (they had starred together in La Stangata and Butch Cassidy) said with infinite sadness: "His presence has made my life and this country better".
Generosity and love of life, two great characteristics of the late actor.
Beyond a legendary career, a great activist for civil rights, ecology, independent cinema, a challenger to the Hollywood drift, has died.
We'll have seen his face splashed on bottles of vinegar, sauces, cookies and other food, judging it a poor-tasting choice, though born as a joke.
The proceeds from those sales were, however, earmarked for his Foundation for Children in Need.
Instead of resting on his myth, Newman chose to commit himself to the end.
He left a letter to his five daughters that said, "Always and to the end, your father was incredibly grateful to his good star.
It was a privilege to be there".
And it was just as much a privilege for us to follow in the footsteps of such a clear and generous American artist.
Model citizen, then, and much more.
What was produced in the invoice factory of Zuschlag & soci?
The hearing on the criminal case against János Zuschlag and associates will be held shortly, on 8 October.
The politician and his associates are accused of repeated commercial fraud committed in the context of a criminal association that has caused considerable damage, and other offences, including forgery of documents.
According to the Public Prosecutor's Office, the money obtained from tenders was used by them for private purposes, and they often certified the implementation of the activities through false invoices.
The state and municipal money, totalling 65 million guilders, went partly into the coffers of the Fiatal Baloldal organisation, partly into the pockets of some people.
According to the methodology, as noted by the investigating authorities, they took the money obtained from calls for tenders on the basis of invoices for transactions that did not exist and the associations never fulfilled the obligations assumed.
According to the indictment, most of the invoices were fake.
For the production of the invoices, the blocks were purchased at the Józsefváros market, while the circular stamps were made in Kiskunhalas.
And to decide in the name of which companies to issue the invoices, it was established among other things during the trip between the hills above the Balaton where János Zuschlag had sent István Lados.
According to the latter's confession, he had to choose between pensions and restaurants.
He asked for an invoice for the consumption, and on the basis of this invoice the invoices were prepared for the calls for tenders, among others, to the Ministry of Youth and Sports, the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs and the Municipality of Budapest.
Most of these are the work of István Lados and András Őri, who, according to our information, mainly drew up the reports needed to obtain the funds.
One of the choices of the "study trip" of Lados was a brewery.
According to two invoices issued by Zuschlag and associates in 2003, the restaurant served meals to a group of 90 persons from the Association Biztos Pont Egyesület.
But so many people, according to the restaurant owner, would not all enter the restaurant at once.
Similarly, the invoice issued in the summer of 2002 to the Jobb Jövőért Foundation, later known as Együtt a Harmadik Évezredért, is full of formal and substantive errors.
A guesthouse in Badacsonytomaj has only three rooms, no more than 10 people could stay there, however, the bill listed 130 guests.
But the imaginative invoicers went too far when they pointed to Pigal Kft., also a catering company, whose accounts - according to the information provided to the judicial authorities - did not even contain documents in the name of Jobb Jövőért and Hoppá.
Győző Farkas, the company's director, told hvg.hu that when he was summoned to the public prosecutor's office and shown the invoices, he immediately realized that they were fake documents.
"On the stamp the name and the VAT number of our company were in the wrong place".
He added: 'Apart from the formal reasons, it was not even necessary to mention that according to the bill 100 people were accommodated, when in total they have 11 rooms and there are not so many beds.'
And the bill was for catering, and their restaurant hasn't been open for a while.
The regular invoice-takers did not bother to inform themselves that the Budapest travel agency of their choice only arranges foreign travel, so they shocked the invoice with a cash payment for travel to Hungary, which was not in accordance with the company's invoicing practice.
Moreover, as demonstrated during the investigation, VAT was also included in the invoice, while travel to countries outside the European Union is VAT-free.
The amount of VAT was also incorrect on the four documents issued by Hotel Révfülöp Kft. in favour of the Jobb Jövőért Foundation, since the VAT on the services offered by the company was 15% and not 25% as indicated on the invoices, and the hotel's employees issued only printed invoices, whereas the invoice was handwritten.
In addition, the "issuers" have spoiled other invoices, in the case of a company they have indicated as an activity carried out the transport of goods by road, as it is known from the procedure of the Prosecutor, an activity that was not carried out by the company originally founded for investment consultancy.
Furthermore, due to formal defects - non-conforming invoice format, false stamp - it was found that the invoices issued in favour of Együtt to Harmadik Évezredért Alapítvány, of XXI. Századi Kulturális Egyesület and Biztos Pont are false.
The same was true of Ravenna Bt. or the Kunfehértó Sports Complex, whose representatives denied having issued the invoices in question.
The forgers also did not pay attention to the fact that the Nyíregyháza HIB Kft. was in liquidation when (2001) a group of the Fiatal Városért Egyesület had lunch there, which is why the curator of the company's liquidation, according to our information, denied that he had issued that invoice.
They have knowingly issued invoices
Another group of invoice issuers is made up of those who were aware that they had to issue bogus invoices.
The Esély Budapestért Alapítvány foundation has issued an invoice at the request of Fiatal Baloldal - Ifjú Szocialisták in favour of the Együtt a Harmadik Évezredért foundation of almost 4 million forints.
Ludovic Györfi, one of the defendants, according to the indictment, persuaded the director of Collab Kft. to issue fictitious invoices.
Zuschlag and its partners also collaborated with the now liquidated Biogate Kft, which in 2003 provided invoices worth around HUF 5 million to the Jobb Jövőért Alapítvány, the Atlasz Egyesület and the Vörösfenyő Egyesület, which were not backed by any real economic activity.
The Commission has not yet decided on the basis of which the budget should be used.
The following group of invoicing firms includes those which are related to the defendants.
For example, Ivan Kubatov, authorized to the address of the general manager of Delta Trió Kft, based in Budapest but not available there, which deals in fuel and motor vehicles.
The company issued several invoices in October, November and December 2005 for the sale of computer equipment, amounting to approximately HUF 18 million.
According to the investigation, Cash Investment Kft. of Kiskunhalas, which has been in liquidation since 14 September 2005, purchased these invoices.
The general director of this company was a Romanian to whom Ivan Kubatov reportedly forwarded the documents concerning the company between 2002 and 2005.
As far as we know, during the investigation, Kubatov admitted to having issued invoices in the name of the company to the companies Atlasz, Hoppá and Együtt in Harmadik Évezredért Alapítvány and the counter value was taken from him.
At the express request of Ivan Kubatov, Romanian bricklayers founded the companies Fa-Bani Jos Faipari Kft. and Jos-Investment Bt.
But in fact none of the firms was operational, because according to the defendant they had not been given work.
The companies were nevertheless useful to him because, at the request of the co-accused lawyer Zsolt Szente, draftsman of the company's constituent documents, invoices were issued on behalf of the companies to associations linked to Zuschlag: Atlasz and Y-Generáció.
In the name of the companies Cash Investment, Delta Trió, Fa-Bani Jos, Jos Investment and Linaxtrade Kubatov issued 15 invoices to the various bodies for a total value of HUF 14,2 million.
The prosecution believes Kubatov pocketed 10% of the invoices and the VAT.
The man also used Szi-Beri Bt. to issue fictitious invoices, fabricated for the call for tenders of Biztos Pont.
Y-Generáció and Szövetség at Modern Magyarországért in January 2006 submitted a call for tenders for the public utility body of the Socialist Party, Táncsics Mihály Alapítvány (TMA).
They also won 500,000 florins each but the sums were not used for the purposes indicated in the call.
In order to keep this from coming to light, they submitted to TMA five bogus invoices received from Works Team Kft.
These invoices were found during the search of Árpád Kemecsei's office at the Ministry of Education.
At the hearing, some of the defendants, as they have already done in the proceeding, will probably report on the production of invoices.
However, the most interesting thing might be if the number one defendant, János Zuschlag, decides to lift the veil on everything.
His confession so far has not been very detailed and although he has repeatedly promised to talk about everything extensively, he has not yet done so.
It is necessary to see whether it is in his interest, it could also be that the Socialists have made agreements with Zusi, who - in exchange for a compensation of 50 million guilders, a large part of the damage - would be willing to be the scapegoat.
Zuschlag could also have been offended at this point, since his requests for a lightening of his conditions of imprisonment, namely the granting of house arrest, have not been met so far.
The perpetrators of commercial crimes, which are not punishable and which cause much greater damage, are free to wander about or at least wait at home until the proceedings against them are over, which is not granted to him.
The psychology of over-bid: Why spend more money?
In auctions, buyers tend to spend more, overvalue the goods.
Neuroscientists and economists at the State University of New York have been able to discover the neuroeconomic basis of this well-known and seemingly irrational behavior.
According to their study in Science magazine, men don't want to be left behind in a competition like an eBay auction, so they're willing to pay a higher price.
The research has tried to trace the neural pattern of this "match" at the level of the nervous system through experimental stages.
One group of volunteers played the lottery, the other group of players participated in a raffle, and the functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI) scans were used to examine the active areas of the brains of the participants in the experiment.
In both games, participants could win money, but in the auction game, where the essential element is to bid more than the other, the striatum under the cerebral cortex becomes intensely active when you lose the game.
This brain area, among other functions, plays a role in the "self-gratification" mechanism of the nervous system.
So the researchers say the reason for the price increase is the body's violent reaction to the striatum.
To support their theory, the economists in the research group conducted a financial tracking survey.
In this investigation, three groups litigated against one partner under different circumstances.
They told the control group what the actual value of the product was and they made their own bet.
Another group was also promised that if they won, they would receive an additional $15 prize.
The third group would receive $15 before the auction, but the group members would lose the money if they lost at the auction.
The difference between the two groups was that one group was emphasized for winning, while the other group was emphasized for losing.
Testing the neurologists' hypothesis, members of the "to lose" group were willing to bet higher than the control or "winning" group.
"These results are not deductible from any of the previously existing economic theories.
The Commission has already made a number of proposals to the Council and Parliament on the subject.
Only the methods of neurological imaging have helped to resolve the contradiction between the two theories, so we have come to a third explanation", said Andrew Schotter, a professor at the New York University School of Economics.
Hepatitis: When Should I See a Doctor?
Almost half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, while chronic liver disease is listed as a leading cause of death in Hungary.
In Hungary the number of hepatitis cases is one hundred thousand, of which only 7,000 are treated: the reason is that many patients do not know that they are infected.
The definition of hepatitis is the collective name for infectious liver diseases caused by several viruses.
There are many similarities between the symptoms, typical of hepatitis and jaundice, but their pathogens and the diseases they cause differ from each other.
Hepatitis viruses spread in two main forms depending on the pathogen: hepatitis A and E through the food channel (e.g. water and infected food), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses through blood and organic fluids (sperm, vaginal discharge, saliva).
It is useful for travellers to be vaccinated against viruses A and B, but there is no vaccine against C.
Symptoms of hepatitis A appear two to three weeks after consumption of infected food, accompanied by general malaise, weakness, abdominal pain and nausea.
Then yellowish spots form on the skin and on the whites of the eyes, faeces become light and urine dark, healing within two to three weeks.
One million people die each year worldwide from hepatitis B, the most serious variant of the disease, which causes liver cancer and cirrhosis.
The main reason is that, according to estimates, only one person in ten receives drug treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have very serious consequences: if left untreated, it can cause cirrhosis of the liver and cancers.
Most infected people are unaware that they have the disease because the pathogens subtly destroy liver cells, and in many cases the first symptoms appear after 20 to 30 years.
So prevention and regular medical checks are very important.
This disease is much more common than average in three groups: those who received a blood transfusion before 1991, drug addicts, and tattooed people.
Worldwide, the number of people infected with the chronic hepatitis C virus now stands at 200 million.
Since even a routine laboratory test can reveal the disease, it is worth consulting your family doctor when any symptoms of unknown origin are noted.
If the disease is recognized in time and curable, the virus can be eliminated from the body, thus stopping the infectious power and preventing the formation of tumors.
September 30 is World Hepatitis Day, first organized worldwide in 2004 by hepatitis associations.
The aim is to raise awareness of chronic viral hepatitis, the causes of its development and the early recognition of the disease.
Does believing in God make you feel less pain?
According to a recent survey, religious faith has acted as a kind of painkiller that has made the death of Catholic martyrs more bearable.
Scientists at Oxford University have conducted an interesting experiment, examining how belief in God affects the feeling of pain, reports Britain's Telegraph.
In the bizarre investigation, 12 Catholic believers and as many atheists were given an electric shock while all of them were looking at a painting of the Virgin Mary.
The results showed that Catholic believers were able to repel much of the pain.
Through the technique of exploring the human brain it was discovered that Catholics were able to activate the part of the brain responsible for controlling pain.
The test is the first in a series of research projects in which academics are also involved, as well as scientists, philosophers and theologians from the University.
The test was carried out exactly as follows: A device that emits shocks and passes the electroshock was attached to the left hand of the subject of the experiment.
The researchers asked participants to focus on two paintings, the 17th-century Virgin Mary by Sassoferrato and the 15th-century Lady with the Sash by Leonardo da Vinci.
The authors of the examination hoped that the image of the Virgin Mary would give rise to a kind of religious status among believers, while the painting by Leonardo was chosen because it did not differ too much from the other and they considered it to have a calming effect.
The subjects spent half an hour in front of the MRI scanner and in this time they received 20 electroshocks in four consecutive sets, while they watched either the religious painting or the other.
Catholics reported that the vision of the Virgin Mary made them feel "secure", as if "someone was looking after" them, and "they were reassured and filled with peace".
Looking at the religious-themed image, they reported 12 percent less pain than when they saw Leonardo's work.
Psychologist Miguel Farias, who took part in the test himself, believes that a similar result can be achieved with any image that has a strong effect even on atheists, but one must find the right image.
"We have to look for an image to which they have very positive feelings, like a mother or a father", the psychologist said.
Anglican Bishop Tom Wright was pleased with the result of the research.
"The practice of faith should change, and in many cases it does change our personality", Wright added.
After the excellent results, the only question remains is, if the faithful are presented with a painting of a Madonna by Leonardo or another painter of similar caliber, what effect might it have on pain control?
Would a vision of a quality Virgin Mary have better results?
You are what you say you are
On its 10th birthday, Google can claim to be both in people's pockets and in the sky above their heads; it knows where they've spent their holidays, which clinic they've been to and what interests them.
But that, according to Eric Schmidt, one of the firm's directors, is not enough.
As for the skeptics who make the Orwellian nightmare comparison, they don't see the substance of Web 2.0.
Eric Schmidt recently told the Financial Times that Google's main purpose is to collect as much personal data as possible from its users and that this is necessary to stick to the original goal of Google's founders which was: "put all the world's information in one system!"
According to the Google executive interviewed, the company, after 10 years of groundbreaking work, is still in the early stages of being able to handle all the information.
To the question of what will happen in five years, Schmidt said he would like Google to answer questions like "what will I do tomorrow?" or "what would be the right job for me?" But software cannot answer seemingly simple questions because it doesn't know enough about users.
Not all Internet users are aware that during their Internet searches exactly what words are searched, from which IP address they are searched and on which page interested people stop after the search.
Using the Personalized Search launched two years ago, users can store their browsing history, see what they have searched and clicked on, which will generate much better tailored results; this same logic is used in Recommendations, where the system offers products and services based on our previously declared and registered preferences.
What if my data is used against me, if they look at what I do? - users worried about Google's data monopoly ask.
In most cases, the online counter-reactions are caused by the fear of the size of the potential power represented by the company, and not by the feeling of guilt, fear of punishment, desire for freedom or even rebellion against power.
However, one fact is confirmed, that all the searched expressions are not only recorded but in justified cases can also be provided to third parties, in such legal cases nothing protects the personal rights of Internet users.
Perhaps the most striking example of this in recent times was the coordinated action against paedophiles in Brazil, in which Google provided the Brazilian government with information that made it possible to identify paedophiles from the Orkut community page maintained by Google.
But concerned netizens were relieved in May when the company - in agreement with the electronic legal defense association EFF - successfully proved the truth in court against the FBI: Google cannot be compelled by any provision of the Constitution to provide any information that the FBI secretly requests.
(At the same time the federal government successfully ripped up almost 50,000 web addresses and a thousand search terms obtained in reference to the upholding of the child protection law passed years ago, but still failed to obtain individual user search lists and the entire list of web pages and keywords going back two months.)
Google's judgment is therefore rather contradictory: those who fear to provide their personal data scold Google because they believe that this will affect their privacy and privacy and start using its services and rise with the rebellion of the multinationals who stand out for the conservative image.
Meanwhile, the American geek culture and the proliferation of enthusiasts, activists and computer users appearing in numerous countries see in them the future generation of the big companies, the "cool corporation", unlike their rival, the liquidated Microsoft as conqueror of the world because of Windows, because both are fighting for the same goal.
This can happen because Google, unlike Microsoft, does not ask its users for an identification code, does not ask money for its services, the source code is always kept up to date and the software package is much more accessible, youthful and cool than the official practice of the software giant.
But it can also happen because geeks see exactly the problematic relationship between personal rights and the internet, which implies one of the keywords that has been repeated more often in recent years, the web 2.0.
Web 2.0 is all about collaboration, about intentionally leaving traces behind and taking advantage of the communication channels at our disposal, and while the dimensions of these change for each individual, the substance is the same: to show ourselves.
A young person can create profiles on several community pages, from Facebook to Xanga, can link them with other services such as Twitter or last.fm that lists his musical tastes, all of which can be entered into systems such as FriendFeed or Blip.fm, can also write blogs on which automatically appear his most recent photo galleries stored on Flickr or Picasa.
Meanwhile, we read numerous case studies from which it is clear that the girl, seeing the series of photos taken in the morning from the common circle of friends, easily finds out with whom her treacherous boyfriend spent the night, or a company can fire an employee because he wrote a sincere opinion on the company's top: one thing is certain, the concept of privacy has now been completely reconsidered.
People who live their lives online make sure to show themselves and so we can formulate the fundamental thesis behind the behaviour of young people.
Those who want to hide something or just want to avoid Google's monopoly can do so (by starting with Scroogle, for example, using Google's search system but at the same time not voluntarily leaving traces).
There are many people who do not register on purpose to community pages so as not to be found, Google's online applications, from word processing to image management and news gathering, can be replaced with alternative versions not tied to huge server parks and that do not make our best profile so far.
Public opinion is not waiting in the wings for Google to pull its claws out.
The company's $156 billion market value is now worth more than IBM's ($140 billion), Intel's ($124 billion) or Coca-Cola's ($110 billion), AdWords/AdSense advertising space is threatening ad agencies' revenues, and services introduced in record time are causing major problems not only for Microsoft but also for many software development companies.
However, critical observers find alarming points alongside all this: the company's top management, for example, has completely rejected the employees' protest after doubling the company's asylum line, has deemed the repeated daily catering to be too expensive, but all this diminishes in the face of the fact that in 2006 Google has subordinated the head of the Chinese government and according to their agreement the company will filter all results that offend the good taste and interests of the Chinese regime.
