The intelligent machine imitates the flight of the stork
What better way to develop collision avoidance technologies than to mimic the sensors of obstacles found in nature?
Like the bees.
In the amazing project presented at CEATEC in Japan, the seagulls gave the initial strategic input to Nissan engineers on how to build the next generation of anti-collision systems.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan has built the BR23C biomimetic robot, a mini robotic car with the properties of bees, with the ultimate goal of creating a system that can scan all collisions.
"Bees fly into their own personal oval space that really resembles our protective shield", Kazuhiro Doi, director of PR technology and R&D, explained at the exhibition.
Important is the role of the bee's eye, which is capable of a 300-degree view in any direction.
Engineers have been using the idea of laser telemetry to mimic the function of the bee's vision.
The BR23C detects obstacles up to two meters away within a 180-degree radius, calculates their distance and sends a signal to the onboard microprocessor which immediately turns it into a collision avoidance command.
In a fraction of a second, the robot senses the obstacle and then, mimicking the movements of the bee, immediately changes direction by turning the wheels to the extent necessary to avoid the accident.
This avoidance, which is different from the present system, is entirely instinctive.
"If it were not for this, the robot car would not be able to react quickly to avoid collisions", explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobility and Robotic Vehicle Project.
It must react instinctively and immediately because this technology corresponds to the damaging and innermost layer of the protective shield, within which collision is currently considered inevitable.
The whole process has to mirror what a bee does to avoid other bees.
This process must be completed in the blink of an eye.
But unlike bees, the deflection cannot go up or down or diagonally, it can only be two-dimensional and in the direction of steering the wheels.
So instead of the infinite possibilities available to the bees to scan other bees, the robot, as a possibility available, can rotate on itself, accelerate and slow down.
The BR23C is powered by lighter and higher energy density lithium polymer batteries, which means that they last longer than lithium ion batteries.
Andoh says that the importance of the instantaneousness of the intelligent reaction is not the processing of the data or even less the ability to store it.
This robot has to process some input in a few seconds and react.
There's no need to memorize them and react with intuitive logic based on previous maneuver data, so it only uses a memory of a few tens of kilobytes.
You don't need a gigabyte or a megabyte of memory.
This is the first step towards developing a technology for immediate collision avoidance which Nissan expects to be installed in production vehicles within 10 years.
Further possibilities of application may be represented by the unification with the GPS satellite navigation system which by avoiding the obstacles on the road leads to the destination.
