The Hungarian Central Statistical Institute reports that domestic industrial sales prices in August 2008 increased by 0.1% compared to the previous month, and by 12.9% compared to August 2007.
Prices of the industry's export sales reported in July 2008 were 1,1% higher than the previous year, but decreased by 3,9%
Industrial production costs were 0.7% higher than in the previous month and 3.2% higher than a year earlier as a result of the change in domestic and export prices.
The prices of domestic industrial sales compared with the previous month increased by only 0.1%.
The prices of domestic sales in the manufacturing sector also increased slightly, by 0.1%, compared with July.
The biggest price increase in August 2008 was in the leather and footwear processing sector (2.8%), mainly handbags and belts with 4.6% and footwear production with a 2.5% monthly increase.
The high price level of raw materials for plastics and chemicals caused a significant monthly increase (1.6%) in the chemical products and chemicals sector.
Prices fell in the petroleum processing industry (1.4%), in the production of electrical tools and machinery (0.9%) and to a minimal extent in the wood processing industry (0.1%).
The prices of paper production, publishing and printing activities have not changed.
In the other sectors of the manufacturing industry, there was a price increase of between 0.2 and 0.9%.
In the electricity, gas, steam and water supply sector, prices increased by 0.3% in August in domestic industrial sales, primarily as a result of the dominant effect of the increase in gas prices effected by the authorities from 1 July.
Compared with the national sales of manufacturing industries over 12 months, the largest increases were in the manufacture of petroleum products (32.4%).
In the manufacture of products derived from metal processing, the price increase was 13.2%, with 11% in the manufacture of food, beverages and tobacco, which account for a major share.
A decline in prices was observed in the textile sector (2.5%) and in the production of electrical tools and machinery (0.3%).
In the other sectors of manufacturing industry, the rate of price increases varied from 0.6% to 9.1%.
In the manufacturing industry as a whole, prices rose by 10.2% in the past year.
Prices in the electricity, gas, steam and water supply sector were 18.7% higher than last year.
In national sales between the target groups of sectors, the largest monthly price increase occurred in August in the sectors producing capital goods (0.7%).
In the consumer goods sectors prices increased by 0.3%, and in the energy and other utilities sectors prices were unchanged from the previous month.
In August 2008, compared to the same month last year, the largest price increase was observed in the energy and after-use sector (16,8%).
In the sectors producing consumer goods the increase was 6.8%, for capital goods a decrease of 1.4% was measured.
Industrial export sales prices in guilders rose by 1.1% in August compared with the previous month, and fell by 3.9% in the 12 months to the end of the year.
