Mp3 players charged, hearing is at risk
Listening to loud music for a prolonged period of time using portable music devices such as MP3 players can cause permanent hearing damage.
The European Commission has issued a press release in Brussels citing the opinion of the EU Scientific Committee on Emerging and Newly Identified Health Risks (CSRSERI), which was published today.
"This scientific opinion", the report says, "shows that 5-10% of those who, for a period of at least 5 years, listen to portable music devices on a weekly basis for more than an hour a day while holding the device at a high volume, risk permanent hearing loss".
"I am concerned that such a large number of young people who frequently use portable music devices and cell phones at high levels of noise may be unconsciously damaging their hearing irreparably", says Meglena Kuneva.
'The scientific evidence shows a clear risk and we must react quickly.
More importantly, we need to raise consumer awareness and make this information public domain.
We also need to review existing control systems in the light of this scientific advice to ensure that they are fully effective and keep pace with new technology.'
The independent scientific committee was asked by Brussels to examine the problem, given the widespread use of portable musical instruments and the increasing number of young people exposed to the noise they generate.
'Scientists confirm that there is cause for concern and the European Commission will now examine with Member States and stakeholders what measures could be taken to better protect children and adolescents from exposure to noise from portable musical instruments and related equipment.'
There is already a European safety standard limiting the noise level of portable music equipment to 100 dB, but there is growing concern about the hearing damage that can result from excessive exposure to such noise sources.
The damage can be greatly reduced by solutions such as reducing levels and duration of noise exposure.
In its opinion, the EU Scientific Committee points out that users of portable music equipment who listen to music at a high volume (above 89 decibels) for only 5 hours a week are exceeding the limits currently in force for the maximum noise permitted in the workplace.
Those who listen to music in such conditions for longer periods risk permanent hearing loss after a five-year period.
This would affect 5-10% of the users of such devices and their number can be estimated at between 2.5 and 10 million people in the EU.
The Commission for the Future of the Capital
We start today, we close in March, we draw the tolls in June.
This is the schedule set by the Capitol for the work of the "Commission for the Future of Rome", which this morning has taken up residence in its new headquarters behind the Baths of Caracalla.
In six months, President Antonio Marzano and the other 49 members of the Commission will draw up the guidelines for Rome.
Once the doors are closed in March, the City Council and the City Council will evaluate analyses and projects, so that they can present in June the Strategic Plan for Rome with the "official bulletin" of the Capitol and its mayor Gianni Alemanno.
'The Commission is absolutely independent and all political, social and cultural ideas are represented there. It will have to make proposals for an idea of the development of Rome which the political decision-makers, which are the City Council and the Junta, can then use.
