The Elites in Danger
The phenomenon was already manifested a few days ago with the vote of the House of Representatives against the $700 billion bailout plan launched by the White House: a significant part of Americans was, and is, more interested in punishing Wall Street than in saving the economy.
As the New York Times reported yesterday, the current crisis is tearing the Republican Party apart, increasingly divided between its old East Coast soul, moderate, pro-federal institutions and the business community, and its new, conservative soul, hostile to Washington and the financial world, strong especially in the Midwest and South.
The soul, in fact, which came to life with the power of the vow I mentioned at the beginning.
The above mentioned example is only one example of the changes, the great changes, which the current economic earthquake is perhaps foreshadowing or already revealing: not only in the United States but throughout the West and perhaps not only here.
In the United States and Europe, the crisis seems to be acting as an accelerator of long-in-cubed phenomena which in the new climate are solidifying and are finally coming to light.
The first of these phenomena is the re-actualization, the extraordinary revival, of the dual category of State-sovereignty in relation to a sort of renationalization of the economy.
The crisis is a crisis of banking and financial institutions which have close links with the rest of the world, but which primarily affect the balance sheets of individuals and families living in a single country, a single State.
This immediately creates a political problem for those who govern it: how to respond to the difficulties and protests of those individuals and families who, by the way, are also an electorate.
In short, the crisis appears economically but politically it is almost exclusively national.
Political internationalism seems to be essentially out of the game or to have little to say: the glaring proof is given by the European Union, which is divided as usual between the different interests and between the different state strategies and is unable to decide on any common political line.
And so it is from the government of each individual state that everyone expects interventions, rescue and recovery plans, new rules, and above all the disbursement of funds: since when it comes to the narrowing it is only the states that have the economic resources, the mass of financial resources that can try to put things right.
And they have the necessary means and the legitimacy to use them: two resources of immeasurable value, under certain circumstances, which probably no market and no international organization can ever have at its disposal in an analogous way.
This new emphasis on the national status element in the crisis is in perfect harmony with the growing importance which the latest economic developments tend to attach to a factor closely linked to this element: territoriality.
Paradoxically, in fact, at the same time that we were convinced that we had entered the realm of the network, of ever more sophisticated technology, of the immaterial, at the same time that we were convinced that globalized finance was destined to dominate the world, we suddenly realized that our future will have to deal, instead, to an increasing extent with those very few immaterial things that are water, crops, oil.
All the things that, look at it, can be transported from one place to another on the earth but are still absolutely bound to a circumscribed space, to a territory.
So that those who happen to be sovereign, certainly have a lot more cards than those who are not, who have the misfortune of living in a place without crops, without oil and without water.
I come to the second piece of news, which, however, presages a break.
When you say territory, state, government, you inevitably mean politics, and therefore leadership.
In this respect, the economic crisis seems to produce two converging phenomena.
On the one hand, the awareness of the objective need for authoritative leadership, the demand for someone who knows how to take charge of the situation.
On the other hand, a wave of discredit for the existing leadership, especially economic, which has been shown to be inadequate and full of shadows.
And together with something even more profound and in some ways disturbing: a discredit, an intolerance, an image of inadequacy, a sense of distance, which tends to involve the entire ruling class in a growing number of Western countries.
It seems that in large sectors of the population, the belief is gaining ground that before their actions are the same ideas as the social elites up to now, their way of feeling and being, their culture in the overall sense of the term, have had their time and are increasingly alien to the opinions of the majority.
The demand for leadership, in short, is feeding underground a widespread but powerful movement of delegitimization of the ruling classes and traditional political structures, which is manifested in the sudden electoral revolutions or the sudden turns of collective mood of these last and very recent times, from the conservative rise in Austria-Bavaria to the collapse of the labor consensus in Britain, to the rebellion of the American congressmen against Bush (and perhaps the victory of the right in Italy has something to do with it).
We have the impression that the traditional elites, their parties, their programmes, but also their rites, their newspapers, their accredited intellectuals, their formats, as some might say, are finding it increasingly difficult to understand and therefore to represent what is taking shape in the deepest layers of Western societies and that the economic crisis is reinvigorating, increasing, agitating potentially to the limit.
In the face of all this, to talk about a "mass uprising" on the agenda would be frankly exaggerated.
But keeping your eyes open is not at all.
The super glue to walk on the walls
Defying the laws of gravity with super glue and in the future, walking on walls like Spiderman.
It is the goal of several American research centers and now a team of four institutes has come very close.
With a mere one-and-a-half-inch-square adhesive, scholars were able to glue a 300-pound [100 kg] body to a vertical wall.
The American journal Science has published the findings of researchers from the University of Dayton, Akron, the Georgia Institute of Technology, and the Air Force Research Laboratory.
The material invented by the team of researchers is an evolution of existing materials that use a particular carbon structure, called carbon nanotubes.
"The glue principle can be thought of as a series of tubes arranged like a stack of spaghetti", explains Zhong Lin Wang of the Georgia Institute of Technology in Atlanta.
Scientists drew inspiration from gecko feet, which are covered with microscopic hairs that ensure that the animal is perfectly adherent.
Tests on a variety of materials, such as glass, Teflon and glass paper, have shown that the new adhesive is ten times more powerful than the legs of these reptiles and at the same time"it easily detaches from the wall", explains Liming Dai, a researcher at the University of Dayton's School of Engineering.
"This material could be useful as a transitional adhesive", adds Liming Dai.
Maybe to walk on walls just like Spider-Man? Maybe, but researchers are thinking of a much less fascinating use, like connecting electronics, because carbon nanotubes are conductors of heat and electricity.
Other applications could be in aerospace engineering.
No superheroes at this point.
The University of California, Berkeley, is also working on a new adhesive.
In an article in the journal of the American Chemical Society, California researchers presented a hair-like microfibre adhesive that self-cleans from dust when moving on a surface to maintain perfect adhesion at all times.
Medicines: never with fruit juices
Watch out for the grapefruit juice, orange juice and apple juice.
These drinks, consumed mainly in summer because they quench thirst and are rich in vitamins, if taken at the same time as certain life-saving medicines alter their absorption, amplifying or decreasing their effectiveness, depending on the case, with serious consequences for health.
The European Commission has recently published a report on the use of the term 'medical' in the context of the European Union's action in the field of health and safety at work.
Grapefruit juice had already come under fire for being responsible for increasing the effects of certain antiarrhythmic, antibiotic, anxiolytic, antihistamine and neurological drugs to levels believed to be toxic.
The Italian Medicines Agency itself announced the news in a newsletter two years ago, warning doctors and patients not to underestimate the danger of this mix and to be careful what they drink when taking medicines such as Diazepam or Metadone.
Not just apple juice - Experts say that orange juice and apple juice also contain substances that inhibit medication.
Along the list of active ingredients inhibited by grapefruit and other juices.
Hence the appeal of Michele Carruba, director of the pharmacology department of the State University of Milan: "These discoveries are usually immediately reported to the various international and national pharmaceutical agencies, which may take steps to change the information notes on medicines.
So always read the leaflets of the medicines you take and if there is something that is not clear to us, do not be impressed but ask the doctor or pharmacist for clarification" the expert stressed to the Ansa agency.
