Open Office, here is the third edition of the "anti-Microsoft" package
It's the day of the release of OpenOffice.org 3.0, the open source personal productivity suite that aims to reach more and more users, from home to office, from professionals to public administration, as a free alternative to the more popular Microsoft Office.
After almost a year of work by volunteer developers, supported by SUN Microsystem, the new Open Office is shown to the public with several new features: the welcome screen and the revised interface and made less spartan, other more substantial ones are added such as native compatibility for the Apple Mac OS X operating system and support for the new ODF (Open Document Format) 1.2, the latest ISO standard version.
Attention also paid to interoperability with the Office 2007 suite, Open Office is able to open documents with the new Microsoft extension (.docx, .xlsx, .pptx).
Some of the specific features of some modules are interesting, such as the ability to reduce the size of PowerPoint presentations, useful for example to send them by e-mail, or the ability to import PDF files into the graphic processing module, while preserving the original appearance of the page.
On this front, "hybrid PDF" documents can be created, combining the typical graphics of the Adobe format with the elements of a spreadsheet or a word processor.
Collaboration is an element that has received several improvements within the applications: in the spreadsheet, you can intervene several times between different users, avoiding conflicts on changes, in the word processor, each collaborator is assigned a color in the comments for better recognition during the revision phase.
Some companies are also working to bring some OpenOffice features to the web (on the cloud), and should release the final result in the coming weeks.
The Italian version can be downloaded from http://it.openoffice.org/download/3.0.0/download300.html and is added to the English version that was on the mirrors on Friday.
In addition to Windows and Mac OS, the suite is also available for the Linux operating system.
The installation CD can also be sent to your home or workplace on request.
And if the topic of free can be a drag for the diffusion in the homes, it is precisely in the business environment that the Open Office suite tries the big bet, being able to already count on several projects realized in the public administration and in schools.
And there is no shortage of organisations offering training, advice and support services which are ideal for small and medium-sized enterprises, and which could open up business prospects.
Open Office consists of five main modules: Writer, for the corresponding video writing of Word; Calc, is the spreadsheet that aims to replace Excel; Impress, for the Powerpoint emulo presentations; Dbase, as in the case of the most famous Access is the program that allows you to work on databases; Draw, is finally the graphic module.
The target for 2008 is to reach 5 million downloads, and considering that we are now at almost 3,600,000, with the release of the new version it is likely that we can even exceed the expected figure.
