Goodbye old cinema paradise, cities are canceling the historic halls
The old movie theaters are closing in favor of multiplexes.
"A city without cinemas is a blind city, it's like a face without eyes".
The image offered by director Giuseppe Tornatore effectively captures what is happening in the major Italian urban centers but also in the cities of the province.
The process of marginalizing the cinema, with the birth in the peripheries of the large multiplexes and the consequent death by consumption of the single screens in the central areas of the cities, is one of those events that seem inescapable and incontrovertible to us but also has all the characteristics of a real cultural crime.
"It's like losing a friend, an acquaintance with whom we shared a piece of the road and many emotions", observes the director of Nuovo cinema Paradiso, the film which won Tornatore the Oscar and the Grand Prix of the Cannes jury twenty years ago, and which told the story of a provincial cinema hall and nostalgia for a way of living cinema that was perhaps lost forever.
The figures provided by Anec, the main exhibitors' association, speak plainly: in the last five years 316 traditional cinemas have closed their doors, and the biggest losers are mainly the cinemas in the main cities: 10 fewer in Florence, 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 fewer in Turin, 5 in Palermo.
The regions most affected by the closures were Emilia-Romagna with 82 single-screen cinemas lost, followed by Tuscany (44) and Lombardy (41).
And to prove that the first responsible for their disappearance is the advent of multiplex, these are the three Italian regions that have registered the largest number of new multiplex cinemas: 195 more screens in Lombardy in the last five years, 81 in both Tuscany and Emilia-Romagna.
The Italian business has developed irrationally, says Paolo Protti, president of Anec, "It is useful to build new structures but it is necessary to guarantee the survival of existing ones, because when a city hall closes, not all its patrons are willing to move to the multiplex.
Not to mention the lack of funds for the fund for the trainers: the state's pre-debit is about 10 million euros.
It is shameful, from an ethical and moral point of view, that the government does not respect the existing laws.
The sector would need between 16 and 18 million euros a year to support it.
Interesting is the case of Bologna, the first Italian city that, worried about the closures, decided to run for cover with the signing of a protocol between the Municipality and Anec, the first of its kind in Italy, to protect and promote single-screen cinemas both in the historic center and in the periphery.
The rules include tax relief for operators and mobility benefits for the public: spectators will be able to enter the restricted traffic area and will have special rates for parking and in some car parks.
"It's an initiative I like", says Giuseppe Tornatore, "and I hope other cities will follow Bologna's example and put other measures in place.
To counter the overwhelming power of multiplexes, traditional theaters must also improve the quality of sound and picture, for today's audiences are more demanding.
The defence of traditional cinema is a theme that has always been important to me: the closure of the Supercinema in Bagheria, the place of my childhood and adolescence, was the spark that convinced me to make "Nuovo cinema Paradiso", which I had been thinking about for 10 years.
I've lived in Rome for 25 years, and when I pass the Rialto or the Quirinale on the now closed Via Nazionale, where I've lived so many shared emotions, I turn the other way to avoid seeing the black boards covered in dust.
