The accusations that the magistrates of the Antimafia Directorate of Calabria are directing to the mayor and deputy mayor of Gioia Tauro Giorgio Dal Torrione and Rosario Schiavone, and the mayor of Rosarno Carlo Martelli, arrested this morning for outside competition in a mafia association, are heavy.
Also in custody is Gioacchino Piromalli, the former mediator between the clan and the public administration, and his nephew, the lawyer, namesake of the boss, already convicted of association for mafia-style crime, sentenced to pay 10 million euros.
"In defiance of any legal and moral norms, as well as common sense", the prosecutors write, the two local governments had expressed their willingness to pay for consultations with Piromalli's lawyer.
"The council would thus be allowed", the judges write, "to officially enter the municipalities, thus facilitating the already considerable possibilities of control and direction of the public administration".
The president of the Calabrian regional council, Agazio Loiero, does not hide that "there are several collusions between local authorities and organized crime" in his region: "There are areas where the mafia intensity is stronger than in others, where collusion is almost inevitable.
But there are many local politicians who resist the pressures of the 'ndrangheta, heroes who keep themselves clean".
The arrests this morning follow those last July, when the police announced that they had beheaded Piromalli.
Since the end of last April, the municipal council of Gioia Tauro was dissolved but already in 1991, and always for presumed conditioning between organized crime and local administration, local politicians had been relieved of the task of administering the municipality.
Giorgio Dal Torrione, mayor of Udc at the time of its dissolution, had been elected leader of a centre-right coalition following the May 2006 ballot.
He shouted into a frenzy when the Prefecture ordered the dissolution of the town council.
He called in question the then Deputy Minister of the Interior Marco Minniti, accusing him of having designed everything for a political issue, but the judges, in the arrest warrant signed this morning, explain that the Piromalli gang had even come to ask for the variation of the A3 project.
From the environmental interceptions ordered against Dal Torrione, write the PM, it emerged "the willingness to marry the needs of an entrepreneur, representative of a larger group notoriously close to the Piromalli, standardizing the choices of the public administration to the interests of the cosca".
When the energy comes from the waves, now the big guys are coming out.
It is an unknown deposit, occupying over 70 percent of the planet's surface, and it is now being discovered by the world's major energy companies.
Waves, currents, tides are the new renewable resources that they've got their eyes on, and now they're trying to get their hands on, giants like Chevron.
The possibility of extracting energy from the movements of the sea has been studied for a hundred years now and in the 1970s, at the same time as the first oil crisis, the research intensified.
When the price of oil fell, around 1980, the idea of harnessing marine energy was put aside, but now environmental concerns and the new oil surge are giving the sector a boost.
The World Energy Council (WEC) in London estimated in 2007 that 15 percent of the world's electricity demand could be met by offshore wind turbines.
This would be twice as much as is currently produced by nuclear power plants.
And then there'd be tides and currents.
Colossians to the attack.
The first company to bet on marine energy was Enersis, which in 2005 signed an agreement to build a plant in northern Portugal.
When the deal was announced, it seemed like a revolutionary step.
Two years later, more and more companies are betting on marine energy, and these companies have always been committed to conventional energy.
"Chevron is studying ocean energy technologies", a spokesman for a subsidiary of the U.S. oil giant told the Wall Street Journal, "and is considering cooperating with us".
The cooperation in question concerns the obtaining of a permit from the US Energy Commission, which is necessary for the start of a project to exploit marine energy in Alaska.
This is a sign of something, especially when you consider that it is in Alaska that the United States continues to extract oil and that President Bush recently launched a plan for new drilling.
In addition to Chevron, Verdant Power Inc. of New York and Ocean Power of New Jersey are pursuing the path of energy from the sea, and the sums invested so far, although not known in detail, indicate a growing interest, according to observers.
Technology to be refined.
Experts say the technology is still in its infancy, not least because marine energy is not the only source of environmental concern.
So far, plants like the one in Portugal or some in Scotland are small and do not seem to cause major problems for the ecosystem.
However, large-scale energy production requires the use of technologies with a greater environmental impact.
And the choices are different: Ocean Power, for example, uses a system of interconnected buoys.
The thrust of the waves, which moves the buoys up and down, is converted into hydraulic pressure by pistons and cylinders inside the floats.
The pressure drives a turbine that in turn powers a generator.
Electricity is sent to shore through submarine cables.
Right now, there are four of these plants in the pipeline, waiting for federal approval only, and some of the energy could be used for a military installation.
Verdant Power, on the other hand, already produces power for a shopping mall and a parking lot using six underwater turbines in New York's East River.
The movement of water at high tide turns the turbine blades, creating a rotating motion that powers a generator.
La Verdant said he has a long list of clients waiting for the necessary permits to use the energy.
After the waves, the tides.
Of particular interest, say the Institute for Electrical Energy Research, is the potential of tides at this time.
Although it is an intermittent phenomenon, the tide is more predictable than the wind, the sun, or the waves and is therefore more reliable as a source of energy.
It is in tidal energy that states like New York, Maine and Alaska, along with others that face the coast, have already invested 7.5 million dollars in 2008 and are planning investments of up to 35 million for 2009.
